(173, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Pengolahan Air Gambut Menjadi Air Bersih Menggunakan Reverse Osmosis untuk Kebutuhan Masyarakat Desa Danau Lamo', '1. Elma Mutmainnah\n2. Freddy Ilfan\n3. Winny Laura Christina Hutagalung\n4. Nadra Rahayu Faradilla\n5. Tri Marcelia Hijrani', 'Department of Environmental Engineering, Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi, Jambi, Indonesia', 'The village of Danau Lamo in Muaro Jambi Regency faces a serious challenge regarding water quality, where main water sources such as wells and rivers have been contaminated by peat water. This water, used for daily needs, has poor physical characteristics, such as a reddish-brown color, unpleasant odor, and slightly oily texture, often leading to health problems, particularly diarrhea in children. This research aims to treat peat water to produce clean water suitable for daily use using reverse osmosis (RO) technology, in accordance with the clean water quality standards set by the Indonesian Ministry of Health Regulation Number 32 of 2017. The applied method includes a coagulation-flocculation process using a bio-coagulant derived from mung bean powder, followed by filtration and purification using the RO OxFIL 400 GPD unit. Test results indicate a significant improvement in water quality, with physical parameters such as pH 6.6, TDS 97 mg/L, turbidity < 1.80 NTU, and water color < 3.47 TCU approaching standard quality benchmarks. Reverse Osmosis technology has proven effective in removing contaminants and producing water suitable for daily needs, thus offering a solution to the water quality issue in Danau Lamo Village.', 'Clean Water, Peat Water, Reverse Osmosis, Water Treatment', 'Elma Mutmainnah', 199, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS173-Elma Mutmainnah.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS173-Elma Mutmainnah.pdf', '2024-08-26 10:16:24', '2024-09-12 05:13:34'),
(174, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Biosorbent From Uncharred Dry Leaves of Ficus Nota (Blanco) Merr. For Nickel (II) Removal in Wastewater', '*1) Joshua B. Bufi 2) Samuel Omar S. Gerio 3) Manuel Bayani S. Bukas 4) Maria Teresa M. Mina', '1)Kalinisan Chemical Corp., Cavite, Philippines 2)Camarines Norte, Philippines  3)A THPAL Nickel Corp. Surigao Del Norte, Philippines  4) Bicol University College of Engineering, Legazpi City, Albay, Philippines', 'The mining sector is facing increasing demands to adopt environmentally-friendly practices due to growing concerns about the negative impacts of its operations on the environment and local communities. As a result, the industry is actively exploring ways to reduce water usage and improve the handling of wastewater This situation has led to the development of improved mineral processing techniques and the integration of innovative approaches to treating wastewater\nThe utilization of biosorbent, derived from uncharred dry leaves of Ficus nota (blanco) merr, has been found to be a proficient adsorbent for the elimination of nickel (II) from polluted water It was found that in this study the adsorption process is most efficient at pH 4.5 based on the one-factor graph. Percent removal is decreasing beyond pH 7 because of the presence of nickel hydroxide precipitation. It was discovered that a high amount of sorbent dosage increases the percent removal of nickel in the aqueous solution. It was also found that as the initial concentration increases, the percent removal of nickel decreases because the capacity of the treatment process to remove nickel from the wastewater becomes overwhelmed as the concentruuation of nickel increases\nThis study examines the feasibility of using biosorbent made from uncharred dry leaves of Ficus nota (blanco) merr. to remove Nickel (II) from wastewater. The researchers aim to find a different use for uncharred dry leaves of Ficus nota (blanco) merr as a means of reducing waste disposal. The study offers potential solutions to combat Nickel (II) pollution in mining wastewater, while also promoting sustainable waste management practices.\n', 'biosorbent, ficus nota, adsorption', 'Maria Teresa M. Mina', 200, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS174-Maria Teresa M. Mina.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS174-Maria Teresa M. Mina.pdf', '2024-09-04 07:03:36', '2024-10-15 07:46:45'),
(175, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Geotechnical Parametric Estimation and Susceptibility Analysis of Bicol University East Campus, Legazpi City, Albay, Philippines', '1), Anna G. Bilaro, 2 2) Amelia B. Gonzales', 'Bicol University ', 'Aside from natural calamities, susceptibility of the area in terms of geotechnical hazards poses also a major risk in maintaining area’s public safety and its ability to economic development. Infrastructures must be built robustly to achieve sustainable and disaster resilient structures. It is essential that geotechnical aspects of structures be studied to comprehend the substrata. Research study aimed to determine shear strength parameters, evaluate bearing capacity, and assess the susceptibility against liquefaction potential/ or settlement. Field and laboratory tests were conducted determining soil properties. Data analysis was done using correlation and empirical equations alongside with NSCP. Susceptibility to geotechnical hazards were done using SPT and laboratory findings. Soil was consistently determined to be silty sand with varying shear strength for each borehole. Depth and composition of soil varies, with wide range of soil carrying capacity. BH04 had the highest likelihood of liquefaction, FS < 1.0. Settlement analysis shows high value of settlement for BH04. Foundation structure must be built robustly in BH04 to compensate the lower value of bearing capacity and susceptibility to liquefaction and settlement. The significance of thorough geotechnical studies for infrastructure sustainability and disaster resilience are essential for boosting the resilience of infrastructure and encouraging sustainable development. ', 'Geotechnical, borehole, soil properties, settlement, liquefaction', 'AMELIA B. GONZALES', 202, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS175-AMELIA B. GONZALES.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS175-AMELIA B. GONZALES.pdf', '2024-09-05 15:02:24', '2024-10-15 07:53:57'),
(176, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'Optimization of Sustainable Empty Fruit Bunches as Heterogeneous Catalysts in Biodiesel Production: A Study of Modifications and Performance', 'Reno Fitriyanti\nSusila Arita\nLeily Nurul Komariah', 'Universitas Sriwijaya\nUniversitas PGRI Palembang', 'The growing demand for renewable energy has increased the need for sustainable catalysts. These catalysts are crucial in biodiesel production as they enhance reaction rates and selectivity, thus improving efficiency and reducing costs. Empty Fruit Bunches (EFB), a form of solid waste from the palm oil industry, are underutilized despite their potential as a valuable resource. This review explores the potential of EFB as a heterogeneous catalyst for biodiesel production. It leverages the high potassium content of EFB as a promising source of K₂O. Processing EFB at low combustion temperatures is essential to preserve potassium. This preservation enhances the catalytic performance. Various modifications have been investigated to further improve EFB’s effectiveness. These include acid and base-impregnated catalysts, magnetic catalysts, bifunctional catalysts, and nano-catalysts. Biodiesel production using EFB catalysts has achieved a conversion rate of 98%. This demonstrates significant potential in supporting the circular bioeconomy. This approach not only  transforms agricultural waste into valuable catalysts but also reduces environmental impact and adds economic value. However, challenges such as optimizing processing conditions, scaling up production, and ensuring consistent catalyst quality remain. Further research into more efficient and cost-effective processing methods is crucial for advancing the use of EFB catalyst in industrial applications.', 'EFB, Catalyst, Biodiesel, Modification, Sustainability', 'RENO FITRIYANTI', 204, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS176-RENO FITRIYANTI.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS176-RENO FITRIYANTI.pdf', '2024-09-08 14:34:29', '2024-09-12 05:20:12'),
(177, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Optimizing Chinese Cabbage (Brassica chinensis var parachinensis) Growth and Yield in Sandy Soils Through Various Viofertilizatio Approaches', 'Syarafina Ratna Putri (ab), Septy Wulan Cahyani (b), Ayu Ratri Wardyaningrum (b), Bella Meyliana Effendi (b).', '(a) Doctoral Program, Faculty of Biology, Universitas Gadjah Mada, Sleman, DI Yogyakarta, Indonesia. \n(b) Department of Microbiology and Product Development Laboratory, PT. Indoraya Mitra Persada 168, Sleman, DI Yogyakarta, Indonesia. \n', 'Agricultural use of sandy soils in Indonesia presents significant challenges due to their low water retention capacity and limited nutrient availability. This study evaluates the impact of various fertilization strategies, particularly focusing on the formulation of Plant Growth-Promoting Rhizobacteria (PGPR), on the growth and yield of Chinese cabbage (Brassica chinensis var. parachinensis) grown in sandy soils. Four fertilization treatments were assessed: conventional chemical fertilizer (NPK), NPK coated with liquid biofertilizer, two formulations of biofertilizer combined with soil amendments, and pure biofertilizer application. The results indicate that the combination of soil amendments with biofertilizer (M) significantly improved all growth parameters, including plant height (45.2 cm), leaf count (33.29 leaves), leaf size (length and width), and flower count. This treatment also achieved the highest plant biomass (196.5 g) and total yield (23,616 kg/200 m²), outperforming the conventional NPK treatment, which had the lowest values in all growth and yield parameters. The integration of soil amendments with biofertilizer (M) enhanced soil microbial activity and nutrient bioavailability, optimizing growth conditions for crops in sandy soils. These findings highlight the need for developing more effective and sustainable fertilization strategies to boost crop productivity in sandy soils while reducing reliance on conventional chemical fertilizers.', 'Chinese cabbage, Sandy soils, Plant Growth-Promoting Rhizobacteria, Biofertilizer, Sustainable agriculture.', 'Syarafina Ratna Putri', 207, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS177-Syarafina Ratna Putri.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS177-Syarafina Ratna Putri.pdf', '2024-09-11 00:39:44', '2024-09-12 05:17:47'),
(178, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Analysis of the Effect of Eco Enzyme on the Quality of Leachate from Domestic Solid Waste', '1.Hariestya Viareco\n2. Shally Yanova\n3. Jalius\n4. Muhammad Naswir', 'Universitas Jambi ', 'Leachate is a percolate liquid formed from the dissolution of organic and inorganic materials in waste, which can pollute the environment if not properly managed. Eco enzyme, as an environmentally friendly biotechnology alternative, is claimed to have the potential to enhance waste decomposition processes and reduce leachate pollution. This study focuses on changes in leachate quality resulting from domestic waste treated with eco enzyme solution applied via aerosol. The eco enzyme solution in this study was prepared using fermentation of lime, orange, and lemon peel residues. The domestic solid waste used came from residential sources. The solid waste was placed into two closed containers. One container was sprayed with 500 ml of plain water as a baseline, and the other container was sprayed with 500 ml of eco enzyme solution. Spraying was done three times within 24 hours over a period of 7 days. The leachate quality parameters analyzed included pH and Chemical Oxygen Demand (COD). The biological decomposition process within the eco enzyme affected the reduction of COD levels in the leachate, with an efficiency removal of 28% compared to the control without eco enzyme. This is attributed to the enzymes breaking down the leachate. A decrease in pH was also observed, indicating an increase in biological decomposition. These findings demonstrate the potential of eco enzyme as an effective method for reducing the environmental impact of domestic solid waste and offer a sustainable alternative in waste management. Further research is needed to optimize eco enzyme application conditions and gain a deeper understanding of its mechanisms.', 'Eco enzyme, Leachate, Domestic Solid Waste', 'Hariestya Viareco', 208, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS178-Hariestya Viareco.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS178-Hariestya Viareco.pdf', '2024-09-11 13:53:03', '2024-10-15 07:43:52'),
(179, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Training of using sluice box for separated alluvial gold towards traditionald gold miners', 'Afni Nelvi, Deri Kurniadi, Annisa Intan Yustisia Rahmalina, Khalik Dwika Putra, Mutiara Salvira, Hisni Rahmi', 'Sekolah Tinggi Teknologi Industri Padang, Padang\nUniversitas Jambi, Jambi \n', 'The gold panning technique used by the Sikako Traditional Miners group is still manual, relying on wooden panning tools. As a result, the recovery of gold is low because the separation process is less effective and time-consuming. The sluice box is designed to increase the concentration of gold minerals, allowing it to capture or deposit more gold particles. It is constructed from aluminum and equipped with riffles and a special carpet to trap higher-density material. The goal of this community service is to provide training on using sluice boxes to separate gold from impurities more effectively, resulting in higher recovery rates. This initiative is a collaboration between Mining Engineering and Industrial Engineering lecturers from the Padang College of Industrial Technology (STTIND) and Mining Engineering lecturers from Jambi University. The service activities include constructing the sluice box, training on its use, mentoring, and evaluation. As a result of the training, there was a significant improvement in empowerment, with participants gaining increased knowledge and skills in using the sluice box to separate gold from impurities. In addition, the sluice box is portable so that it is easy to carry everywhere, especially for new location survey activities.', 'Gold Separation, Recovery, Sluice Box', 'Afni Nelvi', 209, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS179-Afni Nelvi.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS179-Afni Nelvi.pdf', '2024-09-12 02:15:47', '2024-10-24 10:13:42'),
(180, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'Visualization of Clustering and Forecasting the Availability of Waste Disposal Land in North Penajam Paser City and the IKN Sector Using Advanced Analysis Methods and Regression Tests', 'Dwi Arief Prambudi*1), Nia Febrianti 2), Mufid Ubaidillah 3) ', 'kalimantan institute of technology', 'Waste production will continue to increase along with population growth. As the population increases, social needs such as consumption will also increase and this will affect the increasing capacity of storage at Final Processing Sites. According to data from the North Penajam Paser Central Statistics Agency in the 2010 – 2022 population census, the population of North Penajam Paser continues to increase with an average of 3,576 people per year. This population growth will be followed by a large level of waste production in this region. And North Penajam Paser only has one Final Processing Site (TPA). This research uses a linear regression algorithm method to predict the amount of waste growth and estimate the availability of waste disposal land in Penajam Paser Utara until 2029. The estimation results show that total waste production has reached 306,242.4 tons with a population of 1,378,141 people. Further analysis indicates that the estimated remaining waste disposal area has a deficit of 187,161.6 m2. In conclusion, the land area at the Buluminung landfill will not be sufficient to accommodate the projected volume of waste until 2029. Evaluation of the linear regression model using RMSE shows an error rate of 40.27, which provides an illustration of the accuracy of the model predictions.', 'Data Mining, Estimation,Linear Regression, Waste , Landfill / Final Processing Site (TPA).', 'DWI ARIEF PRAMBUDI', 210, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS180-DWI ARIEF PRAMBUDI.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS180-DWI ARIEF PRAMBUDI.pdf', '2024-09-13 03:58:34', '2024-09-13 22:28:01'),
(181, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'The Development of Caffeine Analyzer Device Based on Ultraviolet-Visible (UV-Vis) Spectra Database', 'Sutrisno*1), Samsidar 2), Rahmi1) , M. Ficky Afrianto2), and Lucky Zaher Maulana2),  ', '1) Chemistry, Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi, Jambi,36361, Indonesia\n2) Physics, Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi, Jambi,36361, Indonesia\n', 'Caffeine Analyzer was developed to simplify identifying caffeine content in coffee powder based on coffee variety, roasting methods, and powder size. The UV-Vis test was carried out in this study on 51 Arabica, Liberica, and Robusta coffee powder samples. The results of that measurement are then used as a database programmed in the Caffein Analyzer device. The Caffeine Analyzer apparatus has three parameter systems: pH monitor, mass scale, and TCS 3200 color sensor. In order to identify the caffeine content, the mass of the coffee powder sample must first be determined using a mass balance. Then, the coffee powder is prepared in the box to get the RGB code from the TCS 3200 color sensor. The measurement results are displayed as a percentage (%) and weight (mg) of caffeine content. \n', 'Caffeine; Analyzer; Uv-Vis.', 'Sutrisno', 211, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS181-Samsidar.pdf', '2024-09-13 05:16:31', '2024-09-18 03:14:52'),
(182, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Green Synthesis of Fe3O4 Magnetic Nanoparticles from Iron Sand of The Batanghari River, Jambi Using Pandanus amaryllifolius Extraction ', 'Frastica Deswardani*, Rista Mutia Anggraini, Febri Berthalita Pujaningsih, Aulia Putri Berliana, Lucky Zaehir Maulana', 'Departement of Physics, Universitas Jambi, Indonesia', 'Green synthesis of Fe3O4 magnetic nanoparticles has been carried out from the iron sand of the Batanghari River in Jambi using Pandanus amaryllifolius extract. The extract contins of flavonoids and phenolic acid, where these biomolecules can act as reducing and stabilizing agents in the synthesis of metal nanomaterials. The parameter in this research is to see the effect of variations in the volume of Pandanus amaryllifolius extract on the results of  green synthesis Fe3O4. Variations in extraction volume are 15 mL, 10 mL and 15 mL. The synthesis results were then characterized by XRD (X-Ray Diffractometer) showing the presence of the Spinel Ferrite crystal structure of Fe3O4. The crystal size become smaller as the of Pandanus amaryllifolius extract increase. The FTIR (Forier Transform Infrared) results show the presence of the O-H functional group which indicated the presence of water compounds, apart from that there is also the Fe-O functional group which indicates the presence of Fe3O4 in sample.', 'Fe3O4, FTIR, green synthesis, Pandanus amaryllifolius, XRD', 'Frastica Deswardani', 215, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS182-Frastica Deswardani.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS182-Frastica Deswardani.pdf', '2024-09-14 10:06:16', '2024-10-04 14:17:16'),
(183, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'NETWORK ANALYSIS TO EXPLORE THE ANTI- CANCER  POTENTIAL OF CIPLUKAN LEAVES (PHYSALIS  ANGULATA. L)', 'Silvina faradilla syahrum ', 'Universitas Jambi ', 'Physalin is a secondary metabolite compound that contains withanolides, flavonoids, phenolic acids \r\nand glycosides which have anti-cancer, anti-bacterial and anti-diabetic properties. Therefore, the \r\nphysalin compound can be used as a natural inhibitor. This research aims to identify proteins that can \r\nbe associated with cancer using network analysis pharmacology methods to look at genes associated \r\nwith physalin. The target PASS and OMIM web servers are used to analyze genes that resonate with \r\ncancer, while the STRING web server is used to view target proteins. The final interaction results were \r\nanalyzed using Cytoscape to see the target drug-protein. The results of the research show that one of \r\nthe physalin compounds, namely physalin B, has a higher probability of being active against cervical \r\ncancer than other physalin compounds, namely 0.994 with a molecular weight of 526.53 gr/mol. \r\nPhysalin B may be associated with cervical cancer in the NF-KB treatment pathway. This research can \r\nbe continued with molecular docking methods to validate our research results. The results of this study \r\nare important because they show the potential of physalin B as a strong candidate for cervical cancer \r\ntherapy.', 'Ciplukan, physalin, networking ', 'silvina faradilla ', 217, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS183-silvina faradilla .pdf', '2024-09-14 13:09:24', '2024-09-18 03:16:16'),
(184, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Network Analysis in Exploring Plant Therapeutic Mechanisms Ciplukan (Physalis Angulata Linn) against Type 2 Diabetes', 'nesfitra zakwan zaki', 'universitas jambi', 'Quercetin is a secondary metabolite compound found in Physalis leaves and has potential as\nan anti-diabetic agent. Therefore, quercetin can be used as a natural inhibitor. This study aims\nto identify proteins associated with diabetes using network pharmacology analysis to observe\ngenes associated with quercetin. The PASS target web server and OMIM were used to analyze\ngenes that resonate with quercetin, while the STRING web server was used to identify target\nproteins. The final interaction results were analyzed using Cytoscape to visualize drug-protein\ntargets. The study results indicate that quercetin has a probability of being active against the\nNOX4 protein, with a score of 0.982 and a molecular weight of 346.51 g/mol. This research\ncan be further developed using molecular docking methods to validate our findings. The results\nare significant as they demonstrate the potential of quercetin as a strong candidate for diabetes\ntreatment.\n', ' Quercetin, network analysis pharmasology, diabetes', 'nefitra dzakwan zaki', 218, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS184-nefitra dzakwan zaki.pdf', '2024-09-14 13:27:00', '2024-09-18 03:17:17'),
(185, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Global Profile in Ectrodactyly Research: A Bibliometric Study', 'Firdaus', 'Postgraduate Program, Faculty of Biology UGM, Yogyakarta, Indonesia', 'Congenital abnormalities pose a significant challenge in realizing the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) due to their potential for long-term disability, affecting individuals, health care systems and society. Ectrodactyly, a congenital abnormality characterized by the absence of fingers or toes, has long been studied throughout the world. This study presents a global profile of ectrodactyly research indexed by Scopus and Web of Science with a bibliometric approach using the R package \"bibliometrix\". A total of 1,178 documents related to ectrodactyly were published in 1915-2024, with an average annual scientific production of 10-11 documents. The United States produced the largest number of documents (n=773) among 67 countries, followed by Italy (n=230) and Japan (n=207). The United States also exhibited the largest number of collaborations, followed by Germany and the Netherlands.  Most of the sources and affiliations in the field of ectrodactyly also come from the United States. A central topic in ectrodactyly research is the role of the p63 gene which is responsible for maintaining the Apical Ectodermal Ridge (AER). Apart from “ectrodactyly”, the most frequently used keywords are \"EEC syndrome\", \"p63\", and \"ectodermal dysplasia\". The data presented in this study offer valuable insights that will be useful for further research.', 'bibliometrics, congenital abnormalities, ectrodactyly', 'Firdaus', 219, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS185-Firdaus.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS185-Firdaus.pdf', '2024-09-14 13:32:23', '2024-09-18 03:17:42'),
(186, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Fabrication and Characterization of Hydroxyapatite Scaffold from Channa striata and Scomberomorini commerso Fish Bone as Bone Tissue Engineering', 'Rista Mutia Anggraini (1)\nYoza Fendriani (1)\nMeisa Rohania (1)\nFrastica Deswardani*(1)\n\n*ORCHID IDs: https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9225-6593\n\n1)Department of Physics, Universitas Jambi, Jambi 36361, Indonesia\n*email: frastica.deswardani@unja.ac.id', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Hydroxyapatite (HAp) has been successfully obtained from Channa striata and Scomberomorus commerso. HAp scaffold is a material that has the potential to produce bone tissue engineering with characteristics that apply to specific applications. The freeze-drying method can be used to make scaffolds. It minimizes contamination and the possibility of producing carbon resulting from combustion because it uses very low temperatures. Natural polymer materials from corn starch are used to improve the mechanical properties of the scaffold. Variations of PVA were carried out. Characterization was carried out using XRD to see the crystal structure and phase formed, which were adjusted to JCPDS (Joint Committee on Powder Diffraction Standard), SEM-EDX to determine the morphology and scaffold pores diameter, and FTIR to see the functional groups formed. The variations of PVA give different pore diameters. The increased PVA content caused the FTIR absorption results on the scaffold to shift and increase the intensity. Then, the crystallinity of the scaffold is much better, and PVA is increased.\n', 'scaffold, hydroxyapatite, fish bone, freeze-drying', 'Rista Mutia Anggraini', 220, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS186-Rista Mutia Anggraini.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS186-Rista Mutia Anggraini.pdf', '2024-09-14 15:18:56', '2024-10-27 10:54:16'),
(187, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'Climate Change Vulnerability of Coastal Communities of Albay Province, Philippines', 'Angelo P. Candelaria, Christian L. Baiño', 'Bicol University, Legazpi City, Albay, Philippines', 'Coastal vulnerability assessment using the Integrated Sensitivity, Exposure, and Adaptive Capacity to Climate Change Vulnerability Assessment (ICSEA-C-Change) tool provides impacts of climate change on coastal zones. Vulnerability ratings used rubrics presented to stakeholders during focused group discussions. Scores were consolidated to generate the overall vulnerability rating. These were based on the status of coastal habitats’ reliance on near-shore fishing and quality measures like fisheries ecosystem dependency, population, and water quality of the coastal habitats. Ratings identified 12 barangays out of 23 that are highly vulnerable to climate change impacts like waves, storm surges, sea level rise, surface temperature increase, and extreme rainfall. Results were highly influenced by absence of three major marine habitats: coral reefs, seagrass/seaweeds, and mangroves. Eleven barangays out of 23 obtained moderate vulnerability scores. This was attributed to the presence of marine habitats that although in poor state, may serve their ecological functioning when properly protected. Highly vulnerable barangays must be prioritized in coastal rehabilitation and disaster risk reduction management planning. Parameters encompassing sensitivity and adaptive capacity must be considered to reduce impacts attributed to climate change. Vital information from the assessment serves as basis for developing plans for improving adaptation strategies of the local government units.', 'Sensitivity, Exposure and Adaptive Capacity', 'ANGELO P. CANDELARIA', 201, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS187-ANGELO P. CANDELARIA.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS187-ANGELO P. CANDELARIA.pdf', '2024-09-14 16:09:32', '2024-09-18 03:15:29'),
(189, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'TESTING', 'COBA VOUCHER', 'UNJA', 'UNJA', 'UNJA', 'testing', 223, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS189-testing.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS189-testing.pdf', '2024-09-30 02:32:23', '2024-09-30 02:33:30'),
(190, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'Mathematical Resilience of Elementary School Students in Medan city', 'Suwanto\nHasratuddin\nHermawan Syahputra', 'Universitas Negeri Medan', 'Low mathematics learning outcomes are influenced by many factors both from internal and external students. Mathematical resilience is one of the internal factors that convincingly affects the mathematics learning outcomes of elementary school students. The research wants to describe more deeply the condition of mathematical resilience of elementary school students in Medan City by looking at what hinders and what supports this ability. Therefore, this study is descriptive research and uses test instruments and interviews to collect research data. Forty-four grade 5 primary school students were sampled from five schools in Medan City. The data obtained showed that mathematical resilience ability was moderate, and some were low. The dominant factors were support from people around them and learning media used to learn mathematics. Rewards and guidance from parents/teachers when learning mathematics provide encouragement for students to want to learn mathematics, but because it is not accompanied by appropriate learning media/teaching materials, the struggle and meaningfulness of mathematics is not so visible. So, it needs to be when children learn math need to pay attention to the mental readiness of students and the media to be used.', 'Mathematical Resilience; Elementary School; Mathematics; Education', 'Suwanto', 224, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS190-Suwanto.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS190-Suwanto.pdf', '2024-09-30 04:33:21', '2024-10-04 14:13:56'),
(191, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Utilization of Fiberglass as an Additive in Styrofoam-Based Cellular Lightweight Concrete', 'Yoga Charol Vincenthius Tethool, Zihadah, Radinal Bakri', 'Universitas Papua', 'Lightweight bricks are characterized by reduced mass compared to conventional bricks. Cellular Lightweight Concrete (CLC) is a variant whose drying process occurs naturally or at room temperature. The composition includes cement, sand, water, and a foam agent, with Styrofoam serving as an innovative substitute for the foaming agent at a ratio of 4.2%. Additionally, fiberglasses are incorporated at proportions of 0%, 0.25%, 0.5%, and 0.75% relative to the cement weight, serving as fillers and binders. This research aims to assess the effects of fiberglass incorporation on compressive strength and modulus of elasticity using 20 specimens (dimension 15×15×15 cm) with a curing age of 28 days. The study reveals that the compressive strengths for mixtures with fiberglass proportions of 0%, 0.25%, 0.5%, and 0.75% are 1.75 MPa, 1.79 MPa, 1.42 MPa, and 1.34 MPa, respectively. Correspondingly, the modulus of elasticity values are 3 MPa, 3.34 MPa, 2.43 MPa, and 2.02 MPa. Notably, the addition of fiberglass at 0.25% enhances compressive strength, whereas higher ratios result in decreased strength due to mixing difficulties and non-homogeneity.', 'cellular lightweight concrete, styrofoam, fiberglass', 'Yoga Charol Vincenthius Tethool', 222, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS191-Yoga Charol Vincenthius Tethool.pdf', '2024-09-30 11:32:43', '2024-10-01 22:15:07'),
(192, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Estimation of Carbon Stock in Halodule pinifolia at Andai Beach, Manokwari, West Papua', 'Sisilia N. Y. Mudarehi1), Agatha C. Maturbongs*2), Fajar R. D. N. Sianipar3), Johanis P. Kilmaskossu4), Paskalina Th. Lefaan5), Simon Sutarno6)', 'Universitas Papua', 'Seagrasses are underwater vegetation that possess a high capacity for absorbing and storing carbon dioxide, significantly contributing to the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions. The aim of this study is to calculate the density, biomass, and estimate the carbon content and carbon stock of Halodule pinifolia in Andai Beach Manokwari. The method employed was purposive sampling, utilizing three transects at each station, with quadrats measuring 30 cm. The density of Halodule pinifolia was determined by counting the number of shoots divided by the observation area. Biomass was obtained by weighing the dry weight of the seagrass. Carbon analysis was conducted using the ashing method for each quadrat at the three stations. The results showed that the density of H. pinifolia ranged from 942 to 3654 individuals/m². The above-substrate biomass of H. pinifolia ranged from 15.11 to 43.19 g dry weight/m², while the below-substrate biomass ranged from 18.48 to 86.41 g dry weight/m². The estimated carbon content of H. pinifolia was approximately 19.14 to 58.88% for the above-substrate and 22.42 to 128.17% for the below-substrate. The estimated carbon stock of H. pinifolia was between 663.63 and 2059.64 gC/m² for the above-substrate and ranged from 955.07 to 1842.75 gC/m² for the below-substrate.', 'Biomass, Carbon stock, Halodule pinifolia, Seagrass, West Papua', 'Agatha Cecilia Maturbongs', 226, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS192-Agatha Cecilia Maturbongs.pdf', '2024-09-30 13:20:32', '2024-10-01 22:17:55'),
(193, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'Antihyperglycemic Activity of Kombucang (Sappanwood Kombucha) against Alloxan-Induced Mice (Mus musculus) ', 'Ashif Irvan Yusuf, Ahmad Sazali, Hasna Ul Maritsa', 'Universitas Jambi ', 'The research focuses on evaluating the antihyperglycemic potential of Kombucang (Kombucha from sappanwood) on mice (Mus musculus) induced with alloxan to stimulate diabetes. Diabetes mellitus is a global health problem that requires breakthroughs in the development of effective and affordable alternative therapies. Sappanwood is known to have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties that may contribute to managing blood glucose levels. The purpose of this study is to determine the effectiveness of Kombucang in lowering blood glucose levels in a diabetic mouse model. The study used a completely randomized design (CRD) with 3 dosage treatments: 0.26 ml/20g body weight (P1), 0.52 ml/20g body weight (P2), and 0.78 ml/20g body weight (P3), and 3 control treatments: normal control without treatment (K), positive control given alloxan (KP), and negative control given alloxan and glibenclamide (KN). Each treatment consisted of 5 replications with a treatment duration of 14 days. The results showed that administration of Kombucang at a dose of 0.52 ml/20g body weight was able to lower the blood sugar levels of alloxan-induced mice close to the normal control, and as effectively as the administration of glibenclamide as a negative control. This indicates that Kombucang has potential as an alternative therapy for diabetes patients.', 'kombucha, sappanwood, antihyperglycemic, glucose level, therapy', 'Ashif Irvan Yusuf ', 228, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS193-Ashif Irvan Yusuf .pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS193-Ashif Irvan Yusuf .pdf', '2024-09-30 15:33:45', '2024-10-04 14:16:28'),
(194, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Computational Insights into CO₂ Binding Energy with a New Iron(II) Vinylic Polyamine Complex for Exploratory CO₂ Reduction Studies', 'Muhammad Irhash Shalihin', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Catalytic carbon dioxide (CO₂) reduction proposes solutions to many environmental concerns. So far, iron-quaterpyridine complexes are among the forefront of the best candidates for CO₂-to-CO conversion. Herein, a vinylic polyamine, (1Z,1\'Z)-N1,N1\'-((Z)-ethene-1,2-diyl)bis(ethene-1,2-diamine) (ZE-DiAm) is proposed as a new ligand alternative to quaterpyridine, which offers less structural complexity and comparable ligand position. Notably, ZE-DiAm also possesses higher basicity, which leads to a more stable complex. In this study, the theoretical binding energy of CO₂ with the iron-ZE-DiAm complex, represented as [Fe(II)(ZE-DiAm)MeCN]²⁺, was calculated using density functional theory (DFT). The binding energy was found to be 262.262 kJ/mol which is significantly higher than the typical binding energies calculated for CO₂ interactions with iron complexes that generally range from 33.890 kJ/mol to 125.520 kJ/mol. It shows that the complex [Fe(II)(ZE-DiAm)MeCN]²⁺ forms a more stable bond with CO₂, enhancing its potential as a catalyst in the activation of CO₂. This investigation therefore lays the platform for further laboratory work on the catalytic properties of [Fe(II)(ZE-DiAm)MeCN]²⁺, aiming to facilitate the reductive transformations of CO₂ to CO and other reduced products.', 'CO₂ Conversion, Iron Complexes, ZE-DiAm, DFT Analysis, Binding Energy', 'Muhammad Irhash Shalihin', 221, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS194-Muhammad Irhash Shalihin.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS194-Muhammad Irhash Shalihin.pdf', '2024-09-30 15:34:35', '2024-10-24 10:10:17'),
(195, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Analysis of the Model\'s Fitness of the Modern Test Theory Model in Measuring the Ethnomathematics Knowledge of Prospective Mathematics Teachers: Jambi Cultural Context ', '1) Ilham Falani \n2) Yelli Ramalisa \n3) Muhammad Adi Saputra', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Ethnomathematics knowledge is essential for a teacher to implement ethnomathematics-based learning successfully. This study aims to test the modern test theory model\'s fitness in measuring prospective mathematics teachers\' ethnomathematics knowledge in the context of Jambi Culture. This study is an initial test that needs to be done before conducting an analysis using modern test theory. This study is a descriptive statistical study involving several testing methods, namely the Chi-square test, Likelihood Ratio Test (LRT), Information Criteria (AIC / BIC), Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) and Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC), and Item Fit Statistics. The research data were collected using an ethnomathematics test of seven indicators derived into 43 items. Scoring was done using the dichotomy scoring technique. This study\'s modern test theory models included 1PL, 2PL, 3 PL, and Rasch. Based on the test results, the Rasch Model showed the highest suitability compared to other models. Therefore, the researcher recommends this model as a further analysis model in measuring ethnomathematics knowledge of prospective mathematics teachers: Jambi Cultural Context. Furthermore, this study can provide an overview of further research related to testing the fitness of the modern test theory model.', 'Good of fitness, modern test theory model, Ethnomathematics', 'Dr. Ilham Falani, S.Pd., M.Si.', 225, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS195-Muhammad Adi Saputra.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS195-Muhammad Adi Saputra.pdf', '2024-10-01 03:24:14', '2024-10-15 07:48:59'),
(196, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Analytical Method Verification for Quantification of Ethylene Glycol and Diethylene Glycol in Sorbitol by GC-FID', 'Ayu Nadila Safitri 1 *1), Irham Fauzi Abshar 2 2), Khairul Ridwan 3 3)', 'Department of Chemistry, Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi\n\n', 'Sorbitol is a sugar alcohol commonly used as a sweetener and humectant in various pharmaceutical formulations, especially for pediatric syrup medicines this formula is designed specifically for children to treat various health conditions. An analytical method for determining ethylene glycol and diethylene glycol in sorbitol was developed and validated according to current legislation. This work uses the liquid-liquid extraction sample preparation method to determine the polar ethylene glycol and diethylene glycol in liquid samples. This method includes the application of sample extraction with the ratio of acetone and water, vortexing, and standing times on the extraction followed by quantification using a gas chromatography-flame ionization detector. Analytical performances of the method were satisfactory, showed good linearity in the selected range (R2 > 0.999), and the average value of s/n limits of quantification (LOQ) for EG and DEG were 11.299 and 18.792. Average recoveries in the ranges of 93.9-99.5% (RSD, 1.1-2.4%) for EG, and 97.3-105.5% (RSD, 1.0-2.8%) for DEG were obtained appropriately. The specificity of the method is also good because it is able to analyze compounds without interference from other components. Finally, the present method was applied for the determination of ethylene glycol and diethylene glycol in sorbitol solutions, proving to be reliable.', 'Sorbitol, Ethylene glycol, Diethylene glycol, Analytical method, Gas Chromatography', 'Ayu Nadila Safitri', 229, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS196-Ayu Nadila Safitri.pdf', '2024-10-01 15:20:13', '2024-10-01 22:14:37'),
(197, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Modification of Eco-Enzyme Production Based on Pineapple Peel Waste (Ananas comosus) with the Addition of Ganoderma lucidum as an Antidermatophytic Agent', 'Hasna Ul Maritsa , Anggari Linda Destiana , Uni Baroroh Husnuddin ', 'Biology Study Program, Faculty of Science and Technology, University of Jambi', 'Pineapple peel waste from Tangkit has not been optimally utilized and is still often considered as waste. One effort to improve its management is by producing a bioproduct known as eco-enzyme. The production process of eco-enzyme typically requires up to 3 months of fermentation; therefore, an inducer is needed to help accelerate the degradation of Tangkit pineapple peel into this bioproduct. Besides potentially shortening the fermentation time, the bioactivity of the eco-enzyme, particularly as an antimycotic agent, could also be enhanced. This is because Ganoderma lucidum has anti-inflammatory and anti-allergic properties. The aim of this study is to assess the effect of adding the fungus Ganoderma lucidum as a decomposer agent in the production of eco-enzyme based on Tangkit pineapple peel waste and to determine the antifungal ability of the modified Tangkit pineapple peel waste eco-enzyme against dermatophyte fungi. The research method used is an experimental study with qualitative descriptive data. The eco-enzyme is combined with G. lucidum and compared to a control (without G. lucidum) to test its ability to inhibit Trichophyton rubrum using concentration variations of 0%, 20%, 40%, 60%, 80%, and 100% with incubation periods of 15 days and 45 days on PDA media. The results show that in the 15-day fermentation period, the modified eco-enzyme was not able to inhibit the growth of T. rubrum. However, with a 45-day incubation period at all concentration variations (except in the control), Trichophyton was unable to grow on this modified substrate. This indicates that the modification using G. lucidum can act as an antidermatophytic agent against T. rubrum', 'Eco enzymes Ananas comosus, Trycophyton rubrum, bioactivity microbial', 'HASNA UL MARITSA', 230, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS197-HASNA UL MARITSA.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS197-HASNA UL MARITSA.pdf', '2024-10-01 15:29:26', '2024-10-27 03:24:55'),
(198, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Index of Cultural Significance of Useful Plants in the Kenduri SKO Traditional Ceremony of the Kerinci Community, Hamparan Rawang District, Sungai Penuh City, Jambi Province', 'Ade Adriadi, Revis Asra, Fitra Wahyuni', 'Universitas Jambi', 'The indigenous people of Kerinci are called the \"Kerinci Tribe\". The population of this tribe is around 300,000 people\nwith a clustered village pattern. The Kerinci tribe is known to have rules of life\nwhich has been around for hundreds of years. Administratively, Kerinci has experienced expansion into\n2 Regency and City areas, namely Kerinci Regency and Sungai Banyak City. Administration has been completed\nseparate, but in terms of customs and culture, both are still in the same family, namely the Kerinci Tribe.\nOne of the sub-districts in Sungai Banyak is Hamparan Rawang Sub-district which has\nculture and various traditions that are still preserved, one of which is traditional ceremonies. Wrong\nOne traditional ceremony in Hamparan Rawang District is the Kenduri Sko Traditional Ceremony.', 'Ethnobotany, Kenduri sko', 'Ade Adriadi', 234, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS198-Ade Adriadi.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS198-Ade Adriadi.pdf', '2024-10-03 07:40:43', '2024-10-23 04:40:03'),
(199, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Analysis of Students\' Scientific Literacy Abilities in Conservation Biology Courses', 'Ade Adriadi, Dawam Suprayogi, Andini Vermita Bestari', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Conservation biology is a subject that has high relevance, especially to conditions\nIndonesia is currently experiencing a massive loss of diversity from year to year1\n. Effort\nMuch development of this course has been carried out, including the integration of lecture-based courses\nlocal wisdom 2\n; mini research activities3\n; learning species identification response4\n; integrate\nwith religious values ​​5\n; contextual learning6\n; learning standing banner model7\n; as well as\ndevelopment of a citizen Science Project-based conservation biology lecture program8\n. All this effort\nThis is done so that learning in conservation biology courses becomes more meaningful, meaning science\nWhat students learn in conservation biology courses can be applied in their lives. Wrong\nOne important ability that students must have in conservation biology courses is\nscientific literacy skills. Scientific literacy is a person\'s ability to understand science,\ncommunicating science, as well as applying scientific knowledge to solve problems so that\nhave a high attitude and sensitivity towards themselves and their environment in making decisions\nbased on scientific considerations9\n. The concept of scientific literacy expects students to have a sense\nhigh concern for oneself and one\'s environment in facing life\'s problems\neveryday life and make decisions based on the scientific knowledge they understand10\n. For\ncan produce students who have good scientific literacy skills in courses\nConservation biology requires data to determine the extent of students\' scientific literacy abilities\nthe. Therefore, this research will focus on analyzing scientific literacy abilities\nstudents in conservation biology courses', 'Biology Conservation, Literation', 'Ade Adriadi', 234, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS199-Ade Adriadi.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS199-Ade Adriadi.pdf', '2024-10-03 08:11:22', '2024-10-23 04:40:28'),
