(209, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Paper-Based Sensor for Colorimetric Detection of Creatinine Using  Silver Nanoparticle ', 'Martina Asti Rahayu,1* Indra Lasmana Tarigan2, Munifilia Eka Sari3, Yolanda Wulandari4', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Creatinine is a clinically significant analyte used to diagnose kidney conditions. The purpose of this study was to develop a sensor for the detection of creatinine using filter paper immobilized by silver nanoparticles (AgNPs). Colorimetric detection of creatinine was developed based on the AgNPs aggregation. The average diameter of the synthesized AgNPs was estimated to be around 47,1±0,549 nm. The method is based on the colorimetric reaction between creatinine and silver nanoparticles, where the solution color changes from yellow to dark blue. Its assembly method includes cutting paper discs arranged into several reading units within a plastic pouch, enabling effective creatinine quantification. Under optimal conditions, the developed method allowed creatinine quantification in the dynamic range of 0,5-10 mg/dL, with a limit of detection (LOD) of 0,34 mg/dL and a limit of quantification (LOQ) of 1,13 mg/dL. The color intensity developed was processed in ImageJ software, based on digital image scanning, performed in 10 minutes after the sample insertion. The device is stable for up to one week when stored in a vacuum at 4ºC. The proposed method could offer simple, rapid, and inexpensive creatinine analysis for clinical diagnosis', 'creatinine, paper-based sensor, colorimetric detection, silver nanoparticle', 'Martina Asti Rahayu', 246, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS209-Martina Asti Rahayu.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS209-Martina Asti Rahayu.pdf', '2024-10-09 13:29:42', '2024-10-21 14:30:53'),
(210, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Nutrient Status As A Basic Diagnostic For Revealing Micro-Macroorganism Community of Tropical River: Case Study Batanghari River Indonesia ', 'Tedjo Sukmono1, Tri Suryono2, Dyah Muji Rahayu3*, Martina Asti Rahayu4, Sarwo Edy Wibowo5, Bs Monica Arfiana3, Ester Restiana Endang Gelis3, Wulandari3, Muhammad Harisky3', 'Harisky3\n1Biology Department, Science and Technology Faculty, Jambi University, Jambi 36361, Indonesia\n2National Research and Innovation Agency, BRIN, Gedung B.J. Habibie, Jakarta Pusat 10340, Indonesia\n3Fisheries Department, Animal Husbandry Faculty, Jambi University, Jambi 36361, Indonesia\n4Chemistry Department, Science and Technology Faculty, Jambi University, Jmabi 36361, Indonesia\n5Animal Health Department, Animal Husbandry Faculty, Jambi University, Jambi 36361, Indonesia\n', 'Increasing human activities such as agriculture, settlements, and fish farming have contributed to nutrient inputs that have led to a decline in the quality of the Batanghari River. The aim was to determine the upstream-to-downstream status that occurs with different human activities along the Batanghari River based on nutrients and how it can predict the structure of micro-macroorganisms in this river. The study was conducted during the dry season and divided into six stations. The results of the Pollution Index (PIj) showed that the condition of the Batanghari River was slightly polluted with nutrients. The highest nutrient was TOM with a range of 77,38 – 162,54 mg/l in the water column and the highest nutrient in the sediment was TN with a range of 1,56 – 5,88 mg/l. Based on the comparison with water quality standards, the concentrations of TP, TN, and ammonium exceeded the quality standards, especially in the middle and downstream zones with unfit categories for Class I and Class II. The community structure predicted by these conditions is that the eukaryote group is dominated by the kingdom Animalia, while the protist group is dominated by bacteria, especially N, P, and ammonium degraders. The high level of nutrients in the Batanghari River is a result of the high load of organic waste entering the waters and is worrying nutrient pollution in the Batanghari River as a source of water and biotic life.\n', 'Batanghari River; Nutrients; Upstream to downstream; Water and sediment', 'Tedjo Sukmono', 247, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS210-Tedjo Sukmono.pdf', '2024-10-10 03:11:37', '2024-10-15 01:47:27'),
(211, 'science', 'oral presentation', ' Monitoring Fish and Their Habitats in Klari Lake in the Muara Jambi  Cultural Heritage Area After the Flood', 'Tedjo Sukmono *1), Yoppie Wulanda 2), Lauura Hermala Yunita, \nTri Syukria3), Rizki Janatul Magwa2), Pradita Eko Prasetyo4)\n', '1) Department of Biology,Universitas Jambi, Indonesia\n2) Department of Fisheries, Universitas Jambi, Indonesia\n3) Environmental Engineering, Universitas Jambi, Indonesia\n4)Department of Information System, Universitas Jambi, Indonesia\n', 'Research was conducted at Lake Klari on 16-21 July 2024, which is located in the Muaro Jambi National Cultural Heritage area,. In late 2023 and early 2024, a severe flood affected much of Jambi Province, including the KCBN area, resulting in considerable changes in the connectivity between water bodies. These changes impacted fish distribution and abundance, prompting the need for post-flood monitoring to assess the ecosystem and biodiversity status in Danau Klari.,,The primary objective of this research was to evaluate the post-flood diversity of fish and the condition of their habitats in Danau Klari. Sampling was carried out at three distinct points using a range of capture methods, including gill nets and angling. The findings revealed 48 fish from 8 species, most of which were native to the area. Analysis of water quality showed that the environmental conditions remained suitable for fish survival, with a temperature of 31.6°C, dissolved oxygen (DO) at 4.1 ppt, and pH at 6.77.\nThe study demonstrates that Danau Klari ecological condition remains favorable for supporting fish biodiversity, despite the significant impacts of recent flooding\n', 'Keywords: Danau Klari, Monitoring,KCBN, Biodiversity.', 'Tedjo Sukmono', 247, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS211-Tedjo Sukmono.pdf', '2024-10-10 16:39:03', '2024-10-15 01:47:55'),
(212, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Development of Android-Based Mathematics Learning Media Using Powerpoint and I-Spring Suite on the Matter of Integers in Class VII UPTD SMP Negeri 11 Kupang', 'Marselina Sarlince Tahu*1), Siprianus Suban Garak2), Imelda Hendriani Eku Rimo3)', 'Mathematics Education, Nusa Cendana University, Indonesia', 'The rapid development of science and technology requires us to be more active in learning how to use technology to help us solve everyday problems, especially in the field of education. Android-based smartphones are one of the products of modern technology that can be utilized as media in learning activities. Therefore, this study aims to develop android-based mathematics learning media using Powerpoint and I-Spring suite on integer material in class VII UPTD SMP Negeri 11 Kupang which is valid, practical and effective. The type of research used in this study is Research and Development (R&D) with the ADDIE model which consists of 5 stages, namely Analysis, Design, Development, Implementation, and Evaluation. The data collection techniques used are interviews, questionnaires and tests. The data analysis techniques used are qualitative and quantitative analysis.The results showed that android-based learning media on whole number material met the criteria of valid, practical and effective. The average total validity (RTV) obtained from 3 material and media experts is 4.32 and 4.25 with a very valid category. The average total practicality (RTP) from teachers was 4.12 with a practical category and small and large class students were 4.8 and 4.41 with a very practical category, respectively. The percentage of learning completeness of small class students was 80% and the large class obtained a percentage of completeness of 75% so that the learning media was categorized as effective. ', 'Development, Android-Based Learning Media, Integers', 'Marselina Sarlince Tahu', 250, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS212-Marselina Sarlince Tahu.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS212-Marselina Sarlince Tahu.pdf', '2024-10-12 04:30:59', '2024-10-24 00:30:06'),
(213, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Development of Android-Based Mathematics Learning Media Using Powerpoint and I-Spring Suite on the Matter of Integers in Class VII UPTD SMP Negeri 11 Kupang', 'Marselina Sarlince Tahu*1), Siprianus Suban Garak2), Imelda Hendriani Eku Rimo3)', 'Mathematics Education, Nusa Cendana University, Indonesia', 'The rapid development of science and technology requires us to be more active in learning how to use technology to help us solve everyday problems, especially in the field of education. Android-based smartphones are one of the products of modern technology that can be utilized as media in learning activities. Therefore, this study aims to develop android-based mathematics learning media using Powerpoint and I-Spring suite on integer material in class VII UPTD SMP Negeri 11 Kupang which is valid, practical and effective. The type of research used in this study is Research and Development (R&D) with the ADDIE model which consists of 5 stages, namely Analysis, Design, Development, Implementation, and Evaluation. The data collection techniques used are interviews, questionnaires and tests. The data analysis techniques used are qualitative and quantitative analysis.The results showed that android-based learning media on whole number material met the criteria of valid, practical and effective. The average total validity (RTV) obtained from 3 material and media experts is 4.32 and 4.25 with a very valid category. The average total practicality (RTP) from teachers was 4.12 with a practical category and small and large class students were 4.8 and 4.41 with a very practical category, respectively. The percentage of learning completeness of small class students was 80% and the large class obtained a percentage of completeness of 75% so that the learning media was categorized as effective. ', 'Development, Android-Based Learning Media, Integers', 'Marselina Sarlince Tahu', 250, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS213-Marselina Sarlince Tahu.pdf', '2024-10-12 05:30:06', '2024-10-24 00:29:53'),
(214, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'Comparative Analysis of Triangulation Methods for Optimal Solutions to the Art Gallery Problem', 'Jefri Marzal, Niken Rarasati, Akhiyar waladi  , Yogi Perdana , Hasanatul.Iftititah, Nindy Raisahanum ', 'Fakultas Sains dan Teknologi Universitas Jambi', 'Triangulation, the process of partitioning a polygon into triangles, is a critical step in determining the optimal placement and number of guards in the Art Gallery Problem (AGP). Among the various triangulation methods, Ear Clipping and Minimum Weight are two of the most widely used approaches. However, the difference between these methods in terms of the number of guards required compared to the upper bound of ⌊n/3⌋ guards remains unknown. This study aims to develop an AGP simulation application and evaluate the difference in guard counts for both triangulation methods against the theoretical upper bound. A total of 228 polygons, with vertex counts ranging from 10 to 110, were tested. The polygons were classified into three groups based on the ratio of convex to concave vertices: fewer convex vertices, equal convex and concave vertices, and more convex vertices. Simulation results indicate that the Ear Clipping method consistently produces fewer guards compared to the Minimum Weight method, with average deviations from the upper bound of 11.8% and 6.9%, respectively. These findings are further validated by consistently lower guard counts across all polygon groups, highlighting the greater efficiency of the Ear Clipping method in minimizing guard requirements.', 'triangulation, ear clipping, minimum weight, Art Gallery Problem', 'Jefri Marzal', 239, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS214-Jefri Marzal.pdf', '2024-10-15 03:00:38', '2024-10-15 14:04:56'),
(215, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Hydrothermal impregnation of Nickel metal into activated carbon from palm fiber and its application as a catalyst for the cracking of used cooking oil into biofuel', 'Nazarudin, Ulyarti, Hadistya Suryadri', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Hydrothermal impregnation of Nickel metal into activated carbon from palm fiber and its application as a catalyst for the cracking of used cooking oil into biofuel', 'Hydrothermal', 'Nazarudin', 223, 'not yet reviewed', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS215-Nazarudin.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS215-testing.pdf', '2024-10-15 13:38:32', '2024-10-15 13:59:11'),
