(217, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Photodegradation of humic acid in peat water under visible light using N-TiO₂ photocatalyst', 'Nurul Pratiwi, Gunawan Simanungkalit, Restina Bemis, Freddy Ilfan', 'Universitas Jambi ', 'Indonesia is extensive peatlands, including those in Gambut Jaya Village, Jambi, face clean water challenges due to the presence of humic acid in peat water, which can bind metal ions and form harmful byproducts like Trihalomethanes (THMs) during disinfection. This research aims to develop an effective treatment method for peat water using nitrogen-doped titanium dioxide (N-TiO₂) photocatalysis, focusing on humic acid degradation under visible light. N-TiO₂ was synthesized and characterized using Diffuse Reflectance Spectroscopy (DRS UV-Vis) to determine its band gap. UV-Vis spectroscopy was employed to analyze the degradation of humic acid in water treated with N-TiO₂. The photocatalytic activity was evaluated under visible light, comparing the performance to untreated TiO₂. The results demonstrate that N-TiO₂ effectively degrades humic acid under visible light within 4 hours, especially in acidic conditions. DRS UV-Vis analysis confirmed that the doping shifted the band gap of TiO₂, enhancing its activity in the visible light spectrum. UV-Vis spectroscopy showed a significant reduction in humic acid concentration after treatment. This research highlights N-TiO₂ as a promising solution for peat water treatment, reducing harmful compounds and improving water quality in regions like Gambut Jaya Vilage.', 'Degradation, Humic Acid, N-TiO2, Photocatalyst, Visible Light', 'Nurul Pratiwi', 231, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS217-Nurul Pratiwi.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS217-Nurul Pratiwi.pdf', '2024-10-16 07:58:32', '2024-10-25 02:52:49'),
(218, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'RARE EARTH ELEMENT (REE) CONTENT ANALYSIS BASED ON COAL CHARACTERIZATION', 'Yudi Arista Yulanda; Wahyudi Zahar; Jarot Wiratama; Muhammad El Hakim; Aulia Permata Assyura;', 'Universitas Jambi', 'The global transition towards green energy, particularly in the context of electric vehicle development and renewable technologies, has highlighted the critical importance of rare earth elements (REEs). Indonesia’s coal deposits, specifically in the South Sumatra Basin, have been identified as potential sources of REEs. This study aims to evaluate the REE content in coal and parting layers using proximate analysis and ICP-OES methods, focusing on samples KS100, KS300, and Parting KS200. The primary objective is to assess the relationship between coal quality, represented by ash content and calorific value, and the concentration of REEs. Proximate analysis revealed that KS300, a high-quality coal sample with a calorific value of 6500 kcal/kg and ash content of 4.5%, contained the highest REE concentrations, with Ce at 150 mg/kg, Nd at 91.76 mg/kg, and La at 67.24 mg/kg. In contrast, KS100, with a lower calorific value of 5800 kcal/kg and higher ash content of 6.3%, exhibited reduced REE concentrations. The parting layer (KS200) demonstrated the lowest REE content. These findings suggest a positive correlation between coal quality and REE enrichment, supporting the potential of high-quality coal as a viable REE source. Further exploration into coal by-products, such as fly ash, could enhance REE extraction efficiency.', 'Rare Earth Elements, Coal Characterization, Proximate Analysis, ICP-OES', 'Yudi Arista Yulanda', 256, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS218-Yudi Arista Yulanda.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS218-Yudi Arista Yulanda.pdf', '2024-10-16 09:34:12', '2024-10-21 14:30:23'),
(219, 'technology', 'oral presentation', 'From Bamboo Leaves to Zeolite: Investigating the Influence of Time on Hydrothermal Synthesis and Mn2+ Ion Adsorption ', 'Lince Muis *1), Hadistya Suryadri  2)', 'University of Jambi', 'From Bamboo Leaves to Zeolite: Investigating the Influence of Time on Hydrothermal Synthesis and Mn2+ Ion Adsorption\n\nLince Muis *1), Hadistya Suryadri  2)\n*Corresponding author\n*ORCHID IDs: https://orcid.org/0000-000X-XXXX-XXXX\n1)Affiliation of 1st author (Chemical engineering, University of Jambi, Indonesia)\n2)Affiliation of 2nd author (Chemical engineering, University of Jambi, Indonesia)\n*email: lince.muis@unja.ac.id\nAbstract\n\nZeolite is a porous material with a unique crystalline structure, capable of effectively absorbing various types of molecules.  Bamboo was chosen as the raw material dua to its abundant availability and environmentally friendly properties.  To synthesize zeolite from bamboo, the hydrothermal method was applied by reacting bamboo leaves with NaOH.  The synthesis process was carried out with different time variation, namely 2 hours, 4 hours, and 6 hours, to observes its influence on the characteristics of the produced zeolite. XRD test results showed that the ZGA/Al-A1 sample produced mesolite zeolite, ZGA/Al-A2 produced 4A-type zeolite, and ZGA/Al-A3 produced sodalite zeolite.  The adsorpstion capacity of ZGA/Al-A3 was recorded at 24.92 mg/g with an adsorption efficiency of 99.69%.  this data indicates that zeolite synthesized from bamboo leaves has potential as an effective adsorbent for the adsorption of Mn2+ metal ions.  This synthesis not only offers an environmentally friendly solution but also provides an alternative use of biomass for zeolite industrial application requiring heavy metal-adsorbing materials.  Bamboo-derived zeolite has the potential to become a leading material in environmental applications and filtration technology.\n', 'zeolite, Bamboo, hydrothermal, Adsorption, ion Mn2', 'Lince Muis', 205, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS219-Lince Muis.pdf', '2024-10-18 09:16:05', '2024-10-18 10:23:35'),
(220, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Spatial Distribution Of Rattan In The Customary Forest Of Depati Karo Jayo Tuo Rantau Kermas Village Merangin Jambi District', 'Mahya Ihsan\nBambang Hariyadi\nPinta Murni\nUni Baroroh Husnudin\nNur Apriani', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Depati Karo Jayo Tuo Customary Forest in Rantau Kermas Village, Merangin Jambi is a mountainous forest located at an altitude of 950-1100 meters above sea level with humid environmental conditions and air temperatures ranging from 21,8-27,30C. This study aims to identify species, distribution patterns, and rattan conservation status in the Adat Depati Karo Jayo Tuo forest. Sampling points were determined using the purposive sampling method. At each sampling point, 20 m x 20 m quadrat plots were placed systematically along the transect lines, totaling 80 plots with an unspecified distance between plots. The results showed seven rattan species including Calamus micracanthus Griff, Calamus javensis Blume, Calamus sp, and Calamus oblongus Reinw. ex Blume, Korthalsia laciniosa (Griff.) Mart, Calamus manan Miq, and Calamus castaneus Griff with a cluster distribution pattern based on Morishita Index calculation. Six species are categorized as Not evaluated in the IUCN Red List and one species has not been identified to the species level so its status category is unknown. CITES data does not indicate that the species is included in international trade and is not protected under Government Regulation Number 7 of 1999 article 4 paragraph (1) concerning the preservation of plant and animal species. This study provides an overview of rattan distribution patterns and conservation status to support better forest management and development efforts.', 'Rattan, Spatial distribution, Conservation status', 'Mahya Ihsan', 259, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS220-Uni Baroroh Husnudin.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS220-Uni Baroroh Husnudin.pdf', '2024-10-18 09:48:28', '2024-10-21 14:29:17'),
(221, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Inventory of Ferns from the Aspleniaceae Family in the Depati Karo Jayo Tuo Customary Forest, Merangin, Jambi', 'Uni Baroroh Husnudin\nBambang Hariyadi\nMahya Ihsan\nHasna Ul Maritsa\nJumiatun Nazila', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Ferns have a high diversity of species and are able to live in varied environments. Ferns have ecological (producers, ground cover, bioindicators) and economic (food, medicine and crafts) functions. Depati Karo Jayo Tuo Customary Forest in Merangin, Jambi is one of the forest areas that is preserved by the people of Rantau Kermas Village for generations. This study aims to determine the types of ferns from the Aspleniaceae family in the Depati Karo Jayo Tuo Customary Forest. Data collection in this study was carried out by exploring method and analyzed descriptively. The results showed a total of 18 species of ferns derived from 3 genus namely Aspenium (6 species), Diplazium (8 species) and Athyrium (4 species). The ferns found are ferns that live epiphytically and terrestrially. The Depati Karo Jayo Tuo customary forest is located in an area that has an altitude of > 900 masl so that it tends to be humid, this condition is in accordance with the habitat of ferns. Forest conditions that are still natural and maintained by local people also make the Depati Karo Jayo Tuo Customary Forest a suitable habitat for various ferns.', 'Inventory, Fern, Aspleniaceae', 'Uni Baroroh Husnudin', 259, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS221-Uni Baroroh Husnudin.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS221-Uni Baroroh Husnudin.pdf', '2024-10-18 10:09:29', '2024-10-21 14:28:49'),
(222, 'science', 'oral presentation', '“Durian Sejuk”: A New Challenge Amidst the Glory of Selat Durian', 'Bambang Hariyadi, Mahsa Ihsan, Uni Baroroh Husnudin', 'Biology Study Program, Natural Science Department, Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi  ', 'Selat is known as one of the top producers of durian in Jambi Province, with a legendary reputation. However, in recent years, a new phenomenon has emerged: durian sejuk– durians that lack both taste and smell, making them unsuitable for consumption by humans or animals. It is estimated that around 25% of the durian population falls into the category of durian sejuk. Additionally, the conversion of durian orchards into palm oil plantations has also contributed to the decline in durian populations, threatening the preservation of the legendary Selat durian. The exact cause of durian sejuk remains unclear, but it is suspected to be related to climate change, forest fires, and shifts in durian tree growth patterns.\nThis research is an initial study to explore the phenomenon of durian sejuk and its impact on the local economy and ecosystem. We also examine agroforestry patterns and land conversion, which affect durian populations. By understanding these challenges, we hope to offer solutions to preserve the glory of Selat durian, whether through further research, crop diversification, or adapting planting patterns.\n', 'tasteless durian, Selat durian, land conversion, durian agroforestry', 'Bambang Hariyadi', 260, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS222-Bambang Hariyadi.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS222-Bambang Hariyadi.pdf', '2024-10-18 23:35:28', '2024-10-21 14:27:41'),
(223, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'EGG MORPHOMETRICS AND PARASITES IN MALEO BIRDS (Macrocephalon maleo Muller, 1846) FROM BANGGAI REGENCY', 'Wahyudin Abd. Karim 1 *1), Suwarno Hadisusanto 2 2), Raden Roro Upiek Ngesti Wibawaning Astuti 3 *3), Satyawan Pudyatmoko 4 *4)', 'Gadjah Mada University', 'Maleo birds are a fascinating species endemic to the island of Sulawesi and nearby smaller islands in Indonesia. Known for their unusual nesting behavior, these birds are considered critically endangered due to habitat loss and poaching. The aims of this research are to determine (1) the diversity of parasites in the faecal of maleo birds, (2) the egg morphometrics in the natural habitat of maleo. The fecal sampels are collected from captivity areas in PAU and LNG, then by using McMaster simple flotation methods the parasites are identified. Mortar and pestle to grind the feces, glassware to place the preparation/solution to be observed using a microscope. Maleo bird egg samples were measured using a caliper, measuring tape and digital scales. Result showed that the types of parasite was belong to nematode eggs.  Each research location has different length, width, diameter and weight of eggs. This is due to differences in the habitat of each maleo egg obtained.', 'Maleo, Morphometrics, Parasites, Banggai Regency', 'Wahyudin Abd. Karim', 262, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS223-Wahyudin Abd. Karim.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS223-Wahyudin Abd. Karim.pdf', '2024-10-19 04:53:13', '2024-10-21 14:28:18'),
(224, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'USE OF ACTIVATED CARBON-KOH FROM PALM SHELL AS AN ADSORBENT DYE WASTE ', '4', 'Universitas Jambi', 'In this research, activated carbon was made through chemical activation of palm kernel shells using KOH as an activator. The palm kernel shells are first carbonized in a furnace at temperature of 400-500 °C, then the palm shells are activated by soaking in KOH solution 2M KOH solution for 8 hours. The activated palm shell activated carbon is then carbonized at a temperature of 600-800 °C. The activated carbon obtained was characterized by XRD, SEM and FTIR. Characterization using SEM shows that activated carbon has pores, and using FTIR shows the presence of several functional groups that can be used for adsorption. Adsorption studies were carried out using batch experiments with synthetic Naphthol and Remazole dye solutions with initial concentration variations of 10-90 ppm. The adsorption study was carried out in batch, based on isotherm assumptions following the Langmuir isotherm model. These results indicate palm shell activated carbon can have potential as an adsorbent to remove Naphthol and Remazole dyes in solution.', 'activated carcon, dye, palm shell, naftol, Remazol.', 'Intan Lestari', 258, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS224-Intan Lestari.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS224-Intan Lestari.pdf', '2024-10-19 13:22:50', '2024-10-27 14:44:14'),
(225, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Prototype of Semut for PPEPP Cylcle - Internal Quality Audit in Universitas Jambi to be effective and efficient', 'Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo *1), Ira Galih Purbasari 2), Winny Laura Christina Hutagalung 3) , Ade Adriadi 4', 'Universitas Jambi', 'The higher education evaluation Internal Quality Assurance System (SPMI) is the implementation of an Internal Quality Audit (AMI). AMI is an annual routine activity carried out to evaluate the suitability of implementing SPMI standards in order to maintain and improve a culture of quality in a higher education institution. Realizing the importance of the role of AMI, every university must be able to implement AMI well so that documentation and implementation can be carried out thoroughly against the SPMI Standards that have been set. The mechanism of SPMI is that each PT must implement an activity cycle which is abbreviated as PPEPP. To realize the objectives of SPMI and overcome these problems, a website-based information system is needed that can manage the results of quality control from PT as a result of implementing SPMI more quickly and is able to digitize the system and automate the implementation of AMI so that it becomes effective and efficient using the method RAD. The expected results from this research are Design of a Prototype of an Internal Quality Assurance Information System that provides convenience in the PPEPP process, especially in monev and AMI results.', 'SPMI, AMI, audit, Information, System', 'Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo', 248, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS225-Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS225-Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo.pdf', '2024-10-20 14:44:25', '2024-10-26 11:41:15'),
(226, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Optimalisasi Pengelolaan Sampah di SMAS Islam Al Arief Kecamatan Mestong, Muaro Jambi', '1. Febri Juita Anggraini \n2. Winny Laura Christina  \n3. Zuli Rodhiyah\n4. Hariestya Viareco \n5. Tri Syukria Putra', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Pengelolaan Sampah yang optimal merupakan aspek penting dalam menjaga kebersihan lingkungan sekolah. Sekolah Menengah Atas Swasta (SMAS) Islam Al Arief yang terletak di Kecamatan Mestong, Muaro Jambi, tengah menghadapi tantangan dalam pengelolaan sampah yang efektif dan berkelanjutan. Pengolahan sampah yang ada saat ini adalah dengan membakar sampah secara terbuka atau dibuang ke lingkungan tanpa pengolahan lebih lanjut. Perlakuan ini akan memberikan dampak negatif bagi lingkungan sekolah dan sekitarnya. Kegiatan pengabdian ini bertujuan untuk mengoptimalkan pengelolaan limbah di lingkungan SMAS Islam Al Arief yang terletak di Kecamatan Mestong, Muaro Jambi. Melalui tahapan identifikasi masalah, penatapan strategi pengelolaan, implementasi solusi, dan evaluasi terhadap efektivitasnya, kegiatan ini diharapkan mampu memberikan jawaban atas tantangan yang dihadapi sekolah dalam mengelola sampah secara efektif dan berkelanjutan. Peserta kegiatan ini adalah anak kelas 12 yang berjumlah 40 siswa. Berdasarkan survei pendahuluan, diketahui bahwa limbah organik domestik yang ada di sana belum pernah diolah dan hanya dibuang begitu saja. Untuk itu, tim pengabdian memberikan sosialisasi terkait jenis jenis sampah dan workshop terkait pengolahan limbah organik yang dihasilkan dengan cara pengomposan menggunakan bag composter. Tim pengabdian juga menyerahkan set bag composter untuk pengomposan pada pihak sekolah. Berdasarkan hasil survei sebelum dan sesudah sosialisasi, diperoleh bahwa terdapat peningkatan pengetahuan peserta kegiatan tentang pengetahuan pengolahan limbah organik dan jenis jenis sampah.', 'komposter, limbah organik, sampah ', 'Febri Juita Anggraini', 264, 'rejected', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, '', '2024-10-21 03:45:10', '2024-10-21 04:03:32'),
(227, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'Enhancing Higher Education Quality Through Internship Program Design, Faculty Resource Branding, and Sustainable Entrepreneurial Ecosystem Development at the Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi ', 'Jefri Marzal , Rakhmatul Arafat, Ulfa Khaira, Mutia Fadhila Putri', 'Faculty sains and technology, Universitas Jambi, Indonesia', 'This study aims to enhance the quality of higher education at the Faculty of Science and Technology (FST), Universitas Jambi, by addressing key challenges such as stakeholder collaboration, institutional branding, and the increasing demands of Industry 4.0. The research focuses on developing effective strategies for internship programs, branding faculty resources, and fostering a sustainable entrepreneurial ecosystem. The three main areas identified are: optimizing the internship experience, improving FST\'s image through strategic branding of faculty expertise, and building a robust and sustainable entrepreneurship ecosystem. The study proposes an integrative approach that includes designing a comprehensive internship program with clear guidelines, implementing faculty branding through digital platforms, and developing a sustainable entrepreneurial ecosystem through industry collaborations. This holistic strategy aims to equip students with the skills required in the workforce and cultivate successful entrepreneurs. Through optimizing internships and strong faculty branding, this study aspires to significantly contribute to strengthening FST’s image, enhancing stakeholder collaboration, and improving the overall quality of education at FST, thereby fostering a more holistic and sustainable higher education environment.', 'Higher Education Quality, Internship Program Design, Faculty Branding, Entrepreneurial Ecosystem', 'Mutia Fadhila Putri', 266, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS227-Mutia Fadhila Putri.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS227-Mutia Fadhila Putri.pdf', '2024-10-22 01:26:17', '2024-10-24 05:53:08'),
(228, 'engineering', 'oral presentation', 'CHARACTERIZATION OF SILICA SAND AS RAW MATERIAL FOR SOLAR PANEL BASED ON GEOCHEMICAL ANALYSIS IN TELUK RENDAH VILLAGE, JAMBI', 'Muhammad El Hakim, S.T., M.T, Wahyudi Zahar, S.T., M.T, Jarot Wiratama, S.T., M.T, Yudi Arista Yulanda, M.T', 'Universiats Jambi', 'The use of solar panels to generate electricity can reduce dependence on fossil fuels. This is in accordance with one of the goals of The Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs 2030), namely ensuring access to affordable, reliable, sustainable and modern energy. Indonesia has a large potential for silica sand mining materials with resources of around 25 billion tons and reserves reaching 330 million tons. Silica sand has abundant resources, is stable for use as a heat storage, and requires low costs as a heat storage with temperatures up to 1,2000C. This study uses geochemical tests and measurements on silica sand samples in Teluk Rendah Village, Jambi. The samples were tested using the Atomic Absorption Spectrometry (AAS) method to determine and analyze the characterization of the silica sand samples that had been taken. The quality of silica sand as a raw material for solar panels should contain grade of Silicon Dioxide content of more than 99.7%, Iron Oxide less than 85ppm, Titanium Dioxide less than 140ppm, Aluminum Oxide less than 500ppm. From the test results, the quality of silica sand in the research area has a Silicon Dioxide content of 95.78%, Iron Oxide 17,200ppm, Titanium Dioxide 13,700ppm, and Aluminum Oxide 8,900ppm.', 'Silica Sand, Solar Panels, AAS, Grade, Teluk Rendah Village', 'Muhammad El Hakim', 269, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS228-Muhammad El Hakim.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS228-Muhammad El Hakim.pdf', '2024-10-22 04:40:44', '2024-10-24 04:42:18'),
(229, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Innovation in Domestic Waste Processing Using Rotary Eco Composter Technology in RT 10, Tahtul Yaman Subdistrict, Jambi City  ', 'Oki Alfernando, Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih, Hariestya Viareco, Dila Oktarise Dwina, Rainiyati', 'University of Jambi', 'The accumulation of waste has become a critical environmental issue, contributing to a range of problems such as air pollution, fires, landslides, water contamination, and public health risks. A key factor behind this persistent issue is the low level of public awareness and understanding of proper waste management and disposal practices. This lack of knowledge prevents communities from addressing the problem effectively. To combat this, there is a pressing need for educational movements and community guidance on proper waste management, particularly focusing on organic waste. One practical solution is the introduction of simple composting technology. This approach emphasizes the transformation of organic waste into valuable products, such as compost or liquid organic fertilizer (MOL), which hold commercial potential and economic benefits for local communities. By empowering residents to create and use Rotary Eco Composters, communities can process organic waste efficiently, fostering both environmental sustainability and economic growth at the local level.  ', 'Waste Management, Composter, Community Empowerment', 'Oki Alfernando', 271, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS229-Oki Alfernando.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS229-Oki Alfernando.pdf', '2024-10-22 13:44:34', '2024-10-24 10:11:49'),
(230, 'science', 'oral presentation', 'DEVELOPMENT OF TEXTBOOKS ON FAMILY ENVIRONMENT AND CHILD EDUCATION', 'Akmal Sutja *1), Firman 2), Yantoro3), K.A. Rahman 4), Rully Andi Yaksa 5)', 'Universitas jambi', 'his research is designed to develop the textbook \"Family Environment and Child Education\" aimed at meeting the specific needs of the Guidance and Counseling Study Program. Using the Lee and Owens research and development model, the study involves five key stages: assessment/analysis, design, development, implementation, and evaluation. In order to obtain valid data, instruments such as questionnaires and tests were used, with participation from subject matter experts and students through various trials including individual, small group, and field tests. The research results indicate a high level of alignment between the developed textbook and the applicable curriculum, as well as its effectiveness in enhancing students\' competencies. The significance of this improvement is evident from the increase in the average test scores of students after the implementation of the textbook. Furthermore, data from the Likert Scale obtained from student questionnaires indicate a substantial increase in satisfaction and understanding of the material. In conclusion, this textbook successfully meets the expected quality standards of teaching materials and is effective in enhancing the learning effectiveness in the Family Environment and Child Education course. ', 'Development of textbooks, family environment, child education, guidance and counseling, learning effectiveness', 'Rully Andi Yaksa', 270, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS230-Akmal Sutja.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS230-Akmal Sutja.pdf', '2024-10-22 13:47:26', '2024-10-25 08:48:40');
