(232, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'ASSISTANCE OF BIOPORE TECHNOLOGY AS A RAINWATER INFILTRATION METHOD TO REDUCE SURFACE RUNOFF AND FLOODING IN RT.10, SUNGAI DUREN VILLAGE, MUARO JAMBI REGENCY', 'Bagus Adhitya*, Yosa Megasukma, Muhammad Ikrar Lagowa, Aditya Denny Prabawa, Jarot Wiratama, Arini Anisa Putri', 'Teknik Kebumian, Fakulas Sains dan Teknologi, Universitas Jambi', 'Community Service activity takes place in RT.10, Sungai Duren, Muaro Jambi Regency. This area is prone to flooding and is densely populated. When it rains for an extended period flooding frequently occur. Therefore, team took the initiative to raise awareness about flood disaster mitigation by reducing water runoff, helping to prevent floods. The Community Service Team consists of five lecturers from UNJA from various disciplines and five students, each contributing according to their expertise. The method employed involves raising awareness about biopore technology, which increases the soil’s ability to absorb rainwater. This PPM activity is expected to help address the flooding problem in the partner area. Geographically, the PPM partner area is 3 km away from the Batang Hari River, so it is not part of a floodplain. Base on topography, the partner area is located at an elevation of 12.5m-25m with a valley morphology, causing water from higher areas to accumulate in the PPM partner area and its surroundings. Additionally, the existing drainage and canal systems in the area are not functioning properly, contributing to the flooding issue.', 'biopore, water_runoff, flooding', 'Bagus Adhitya', 263, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS232-Bagus Adhitya.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS232-Bagus Adhitya.pdf', '2024-10-23 06:46:02', '2024-10-27 03:14:51'),
(233, 'ethnobiology', 'oral presentation', 'Ethnobotanical Exploration of Multiethnic Medicinal Plants in Jambi Province', 'Revis Asra, Anis Tatik Maryani, Upik Yelianti', 'Universitas Jambi', 'This research aims to document local knowledge about medicinal plants from several ethni in Jambi Province. Analyze the diversity of  of medicinal plants, processing processes, methods of use, analyze the value of the cultural index (Index Cultural Significance), the percentage of parts used (Plant Part Value) , knowing the cultivation and conservation of medicinal plants by multiethnic groups in Jambi. This research was conducted in Batang Sangir Village and Kersik Tuo Village, Kayu Aro District, Kerinci Regency for Javanese respondents, Limok Manaih Pulau Tengah Village, Keliling Danau District, Kerinci Regency for Kerinci Tribe respondents, Ulu Gedong Seberang Subdistrict, Jambi City for Malay respondents, Faculty of Science Laboratory and Technology, and Herbarium Anda, Andalas University, Padang. This  research is descriptive in nature using survey and in-depth interview methods. Respondents were determined using purposive sampling and snowball sampling. Based on the research results, it is known that there are 156 species from 61 plant families that are used as medicine. The part of the plant that is most widely used is the leaf part at 49.23% totaling (96), the highest ICS value is 72 in the species Zingiber officinale Roscoe, the lowest ICS value is 3 in the species Saracai indica L. and Salvia rosmarinus Spenn. The percentage value is based on the disease, the most common medicinal plant is diabetes (16.67%), and the percentage of the family most frequently used is the Zingiberaceae.', 'Medicinal plants, multiethnic, Jambi', 'Revis Asra', 275, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS233-Revis Asra.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS233-Revis Asra.pdf', '2024-10-23 07:06:44', '2024-10-24 05:52:27'),
