(260, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Implementation of Project-Based Learning (PjBL) for Effective Learning in Clean Water Production Technology Using Portable Purification Technology from Biomass Waste', 'Oki Alfernando, Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih, Ra\'ida Raudhatussya\'rifah', 'Department of Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Science and Technology, Universitas Jambi, Indonesia', 'This research explores the effectiveness of Project-Based Learning (PjBL) in the course \"Clean Water Production Technology,\" which addresses the global issue of clean water scarcity and the need for sustainable solutions. Integrating a portable purification prototype based on biomass waste, the study aims to enhance students\' understanding, practical skills, and innovation in developing eco-friendly water treatment solutions. Key objectives include examining how PjBL improves learning outcomes and practical skills in clean water production, particularly through projects utilizing portable purification technology. The research also seeks to identify challenges students may face in applying PjBL to biomass-based purification technology and to propose solutions to address these issues. Findings from this study are anticipated to highlight the tangible benefits of PjBL in building student competency, critical thinking, and readiness to contribute to sustainable water treatment advancements in both industrial and community contexts.', 'Project-Based Learning, Clean Water Production Technology, Biomass Waste, Portable Purification Technology, Sustainable Water Treatment.', 'Oki Alfernando', 289, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS260-Oki Alfernando.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS260-Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih.pdf', '2024-10-25 23:38:02', '2024-10-26 00:11:52'),
(261, 'bio_technology', 'oral presentation', '123', '123', '123', '123', '123', '123', 290, 'not yet reviewed', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2024-10-26 00:32:32', '2024-10-26 00:32:32'),
(262, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', ' Application of palm oil fuel ash to reduce cobalt contamination in gold mining wastewater, incorporating isotherm modeling, thermodynamics, and kinetics', 'Rainiyati, Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih, Ahmad Riduan, Trias Novita', 'Universitas Jambi', 'The contamination of cobalt heavy metals in gold mine waste poses significant environmental problems due to its toxicity to ecosystems. This research uses palm oil fuel ash (POFA) as an adsorbent to reduce cobalt levels in gold mining waste. POFA was characterized using the Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) method to measure the specific surface area. The analysis of cobalt concentration was conducted using Inductively Coupled Plasma Mass Spectrometry. (ICP-MS). The adsorption process is evaluated through variations in contact duration and temperature. The data were analyzed using the Langmuir, Freundlich, and Temkin isotherm models. The analysis results indicate that the Temkin model exhibits the best fit, with an R² value of 0.9324. Thermodynamic parameters such as ΔG°, ΔH°, and ΔS° were calculated, indicating that the adsorption process is spontaneous and endothermic. The kinetics were comprehensively analyzed using first-order, pseudo-second-order, and intraparticle diffusion kinetic models, revealing a complex adsorption mechanism with moderate adsorption rates and slower kinetics, indicating that adsorption may not involve chemical solid bonding. Research shows that POFA is an effective and economical adsorbent for the remediation of gold mining wastewater contaminated with heavy metal cobalt.', 'adsorption, cobalt removal, gold mining wastewater, isotherm, kinetic, palm oil fuel ash, thermodynamic', 'Rainiyati', 288, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS262-Rainiyati.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS262-Rainiyati.pdf', '2024-10-26 02:25:43', '2024-10-26 02:31:47'),
(263, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Development of a Portable Drinking Water Treatment Prototype with Palm Oil Fuel Ash - Eggshell Powder Membrane Innovation.', 'Oki Alfernando, Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih, Rainiyati', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Clean and safe drinking water has become one of the biggest challenges worldwide. There are demands, especially in remote areas and regions destroyed by disasters, to have access to clean and safe drinking water. These researches are to develop a prototype of a portable drinking water treatment device with an innovative membrane made from a mixture of Palm Oil Fuel Ash (POFA) and eggshell powder. POFA and eggshell powder have been selected for this study because of their abundant availability and high adsorptive properties toward contaminants in water.\nThis prototype device is fabricated with a composite membrane filtration system of POFA-eggshell powder, which can facilitate the filtration of fine particles, reduction in turbidity, and removal of heavy metals and microorganisms. Brunauer-Emmett-Teller Analysis (BET) characterized membranes to determine their specific surface area and porosity. Results: Testing the device\'s efficiency requires that water samples be treated for different contamination levels. In contrast, subsequent water quality analysis uses universal physical parameters such as pH, TDS, and turbidity. Test results showed that this new membrane could reduce contaminant levels to below drinking water quality standards. This prototype portable drinking water treatment device provides a practical and low-cost means of supplying clean water to areas unreached by conventional drinking water infrastructure. The innovation of how waste is utilized creates value addition towards such wastes, besides POFA and eggshell, being supportive enough in environmental sustainability practices. The field test results showed that this prototype could remove most water pollutants.', 'Clean Water Production, Drinking Water, Eggshell Powder, Membrane Technology, Palm Oil Fuel Ash', 'Oki Alfernando', 288, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS263-Oki Alfernando.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS263-Oki Alfernando.pdf', '2024-10-26 02:52:29', '2024-10-26 02:56:39'),
(264, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'OPTIMIZATION OF WASTE MANAGEMENT IN THE AL ARIEF PRIVATE ISLAMIC HIGH SCHOOL (SMAS), MESTONG MUARO DISTRICT, JAMBI', 'Febri Juita Anggraini\nWinny Laura Christina H.\nZuli Rodhiyah\nHariestya Viareco\nTri Syukria Putra ', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Optimal waste management is crucial for maintaining a clean school environment. Al Arief Islamic Private Senior High School (SMAS), located in Mestong District, Muaro Jambi, faces challenges in effective and sustainable waste management. Current practices involve open burning or disposal without further processing, which negatively impacts the school and surrounding environment. This community service aims to optimize waste management at SMAS Islam Al Arief by identifying issues, establishing management strategies, implementing solutions, and evaluating their effectiveness, to address the school’s waste management challenges sustainably. Participants are 40 students from the 12th grade. A preliminary survey showed that domestic organic waste at the school had not been processed and was discarded as is. To address this, the service team conducted a session on waste types and a workshop on organic waste processing through composting with a bag composter. They also provided the school with a set of bag composters. Survey results before and after the session revealed improved participant knowledge regarding organic waste processing and types of waste.', 'composter, organic waste, solid waste treatment', 'Febri Juita Anggraini', 203, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS264-Febri Juita Anggraini.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS264-Febri Juita Anggraini.pdf', '2024-10-26 03:20:08', '2024-10-27 15:09:53'),
(265, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'A Project-Based Learning Approach for Chemical Engineering Students: Waste Cooking Oil Biodiesel Production for Portable Stove Applications', 'Rahma Amalia, Rosmawati Sipayung, Nazarudin*', 'University of Jambi', 'Modern engineering education emphasizes bridging theoretical knowledge with practical application, aligning with industry needs. This study explores the impact of project-based learning in a bioenergy engineering course at the University of Jambi, focused on producing biodiesel from waste cooking oil for portable stove applications. Conducted with 17 chemical engineering students over the 2024/2025 academic year, this project-based learning initiative aimed to develop both subject-specific and transferable skills, such as problem-solving, teamwork, and adaptability. The project involved hands-on laboratory work, emphasizing critical steps in biodiesel production, including transesterification and product purification using both homogeneous and heterogeneous catalysts. Students demonstrated notable improvement in technical competencies and soft skills, with over 90% indicating enhanced understanding and application of biodiesel production processes. Despite challenges with equipment limitations and occasional reaction failures, students showed resilience and resourcefulness by consulting with lecturers and documenting successful procedures. Mixed responses were observed regarding time allocation, highlighting areas for potential refinement in workload management. Ultimately, the project fostered an appreciation for sustainable practices and deepened students\' understanding of renewable energy solutions. The findings affirm that project-based learning effectively supports holistic skill development, preparing students for real-world engineering challenges and reinforcing the value of sustainable engineering practices.', 'Project-Based Learning, Biodiesel Production, Engineering Skills', 'Rahma Amalia', 287, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS265-Rahma Amalia.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS265-Rahma Amalia.pdf', '2024-10-26 09:29:59', '2024-10-27 04:39:39'),
(266, 'earth_science', 'oral presentation', 'Near Field and Static Corrections of CSAMT Data Obtain in Volcanic and Geothermal Area', 'Husnul Hamdi, Doddy Sutarno, Wahyu Srigutomo, Enjang Jaenal Mustopa', 'Universitas Jambi\nInstitut Teknologi Bandung', 'Controlled source audio-frequency magnetotellurics (CSAMT) is one of electromagnetic sounding method with frequency domain. CSAMT is a frequency-domain electromagnetic sounding technique which uses a fixed grounded dipole as an artificial signal source. Based on the measurement distance variation the transmitter with receiver on CSAMT, there are three zones, near field, transition, and far field. In the far field zone the plane wave assumption already admitted so that the equation for calculating the value of the resistivity can be applied together with the MT method using Cagniard equation. In the area of near field, source effects can still be captured directly by the receiver and the assumption of a plane wave can not be applied so that the data must be corrected. Correction data is also performed at the transition area. The static effects could result for two values of resistivity which can cause large errors in depth estimation and interpretation of the subsurface structure becomes complex. Static correction is done by averaging the resistivity curve in the measured region. Static correction can also be done by comparing the data obtained with the data TEM (Transient Electromagnetic)', 'CSAMT, Volcanic, Geothermal', 'Husnul Hamdi', 249, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS266-Husnul Hamdi.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS266-Husnul Hamdi.pdf', '2024-10-26 15:02:04', '2024-10-27 03:13:58'),
(267, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Design and Construction of Android-Based Virtual Reality Multimedia Applications for Muaro Jambi Temple on Local History and Culture Materials for Elementary Schools', 'Dedy Setiawan, Muhammad Razi A, Dewi Lestari', 'Universitas Jambi', 'This study aims to develop an interactive multimedia application based on Virtual Reality (VR) on local history\nand culture using the Android-based VR application of Muaro Jambi Temple, specifically for local history and\nculture materials at the Elementary School level. In addition, this study also aims to evaluate the quality of\neducational games developed based on functionality suitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, and\nusability. Data collection was carried out through literature studies and questionnaire distribution. The literature\nstudy aims to obtain references from books related to local history and culture as well as journals relevant to this\nsystem\'s development. Meanwhile, the questionnaire will be distributed in the final stage after the application is\ncompleted and implemented to evaluate the system\'s functionality and usability. Programmers and information\nsystems carried out data analysis, and lecturers tested the functionality of each software function. Furthermore,\nperformance efficiency, compatibility, and usability were tested using a questionnaire filled out by 26 sixth-grade\nstudents at SDIT Nurul Ilmi Jambi as users of the VR application of Muaro Jambi Temple. After the data is\npresented as a percentage, the results will be analyzed to determine the value of the application\'s suitability based\non the percentage assessment scale. The results of this study are expected to provide insight into the\nimplementation of VR-based applications using Unity in building interactive multimedia applications of Muaro\nJambi Temple. This application is expected to make it easier for parents and teachers to introduce local history\nand culture to children while also functioning as a means of entertainment and learning media. In addition, this\napplication is also expected to play a role in building positive character in children through moral values and\ncharacter education contained in local history and culture', 'Virtual Reality, Muaro Jambi Temple, Elementary School, Game, Education', 'Muhammad Razi A', 223, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS267-Dedy Setiawan.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS267-Muhammad Razi A..pdf', '2024-10-26 22:25:30', '2024-10-27 01:55:30'),
(268, 'renewable_energy', 'oral presentation', 'Hydrothermal impregnation of Nickel metal into activated carbon from palm fiber and its application as a catalyst for the cracking of used cooking oil into biofuel', 'Nazarudin, Ulyarti , Hadistya Suryadri ', 'Chemical Engineering Department, University of Jambi', 'Researchers have been conducting cracking experiments to produce green fuel, testing the cracking of vacuum gas oil (VGO), crude palm oil (CPO), used cooking oil, and plastic waste using various metal catalysts based on natural zeolite, carbon, silica, aluminosilicate, and aluminophosphate (1-21). A review of previous research and literature concluded that cracking used cooking oil with a carbon catalyst derived from palm fiber is the most promising method for further development. Compared to aluminosilicate and aluminophosphate-based catalysts, which show good conversion rates but have high production costs, the use of these materials makes biofuel production from used cooking oil expensive. Previous research has shown that cracking reactions using powdered catalysts are practically less effective, as the powder is often carried away by the flow of gas/fluid from the reactant or carrier gas stream. Additionally, the use of traditional impregnation and ion-exchange methods with standard stirring has been found to introduce only small amounts of nickel into the support material (5, 8, 9, 15, 20, 21). According to literature studies, these issues can be addressed by using pellet-shaped catalysts (22-28).\n\nNickel was chosen as the catalyst due to its excellent performance in cracking reactions and its ability to prevent coke formation. In this study, the hydrothermal method will be tested, as preliminary and literature studies indicate it is more effective at incorporating metal catalysts into carbon (29-31) or other supports (32-40). The objective of the study is to determine the effect of the hydrothermal impregnation method, nickel concentration, and pellet size on catalyst characterization and the conversion of used cooking oil into biofuel, as well as the quality of the resulting biofuel. The study will involve hydrothermal impregnation of nickel at three different concentrations (0.5%, 1%, 1.5%) into carbon derived from palm fiber. Hydrothermal impregnation of nickel will be carried out on powdered carbon, which will then be shaped into pellets (Method A), and on activated carbon that has already been pelletized (Method B). The pellets will be formed into cylinders of three sizes: d8xt10, d10xt12, and d12xt14 mm (d=diameter, t=height).\n\nKeywords: Used Cooking Oil, Hydrothermal, Cracking, Ni-Activated Carbon, Pellet \n', 'Used Cooking Oil, Hydrothermal, Cracking, Ni-Activated Carbon, Pellet ', 'Nazarudin', 294, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS268-Nazarudin.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS268-Nazarudin.pdf', '2024-10-27 01:36:40', '2024-10-27 06:12:16'),
(269, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Model of intention in Using Mobile Banking of Bank Syariah Indonesia in Jambi Province: Integrated TPB-TAM-Religiosity and Trust Approach', 'Lucky Enggrani Fitri, Dedy Setiawan, Faulina Lubis, Aditya Pratama', 'Universitas Jambi', 'This study aims to develop an innovative model that integrates the Theory of Planned Behavior (TPB), Technology Acceptance Model (TAM), religiosity dimensions, and trust in the context of Muslim customers\' interest in using Bank Syariah Indonesia (BSI) Mobile Banking services in Jambi Province. The model, known as the Integrated Model TPB-TAM-Religiosity-Trust, offers a comprehensive perspective on customer behavior and serves as a reference framework for similar studies in the future. By identifying various factors that influence the use of Mobile Banking, this model is expected to improve the quality and efficiency of BSI services. The research sample was selected using the probability sampling method with a purposive sampling technique, involving 190 Muslim respondents in Jambi Province who had used BSI Mobile Banking services. Data analysis was carried out using the Partial Least Square Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM) method with the help of SmartPLS version 3 software. The study results showed that out of 11 proposed hypotheses, two were rejected: (1) the effect of perceived behavioral control on behavioral intention to use and (2) the effect of religiosity on behavioral intention to use. These findings indicate that personal control and religiosity alone are insufficient to influence people\'s interest in using BSI services. Therefore, researchers recommend considering other factors, such as perceived service quality, ease of access, promotion, and social and economic aspects, which may be more relevant in influencing usage intentions.', 'TPB; TAM; Religiosity; Mobile Banking; Trust', 'Lucky Enggrani Fitri', 223, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS269-Lucky Enggrani Fitri.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS269-Muhammad Razi A..pdf', '2024-10-27 02:30:26', '2024-10-27 02:33:17'),
(270, 'biodiversity', 'oral presentation', 'Application of Ethnoscience in the Application of Ber-ikan in developing the Batanghari River Fish Dataset', 'Tedjo Sukmono, Teja Kaswari, Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo, Tia Wulandari, Benedika Ferdian Hutabarat', 'Universitas Jambi', 'In social life, there are cultural elements that play an important role as guidelines for social order. Culture applied in society is not limited to objects, but also behavior, ways of behaving, responding to nature, and even managing nature itself. One of the abundant natural resources in Jambi fish biodiversity. The Batanghari River has a big influence on fish diversity and culture. The culture of fish is still embedded in people\'s lives to this day. Ethnoscience is not just knowledge about culture, far from it, fish ethnoscience is an intangible heritage owned by Jambi. Therefore, ethnoscience and fish biodiversity are interrelated things. They have now been combined in the same information system, namely the Ber-Ikan Jambi. This information system is an integrated information system that contains the existence of fish that can be found in the Batanghari River. The socialization using the application were given to the community in the Muaro Jambi Temple area, aimed at providing knowledge and understanding regarding the Provide Jambi information system in supporting ethnoscience studies of the community in the area, so that it can make it easier for the community to get information about local folklore against certain fish', 'Ber-ikan, Etnosains, Biodiversity, Information, System', 'Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo', 248, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS270-Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS270-Pradita Eko Prasetyo Utomo.pdf', '2024-10-27 03:21:28', '2024-10-27 14:46:06'),
(271, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Project Based Learning (PjBL) Method in the Plant Genetic Resource Conservation Course through a Case Study Project on Plant Genetic Resource Conservation in Muaro Jambi.', 'Rainiyati\nEliyanti\nAhmad Riduan\nSarah Fiebrina Heraningsih', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Project-based learning (PjBL) is an approach that leads to learning by doing, where students engage in projects directly related to real-world experiences. This research aims to evaluate the effectiveness of applying PjBL in the course on the Conservation of Plasma Nutfah through a case study project in Muaro Jambi. The focus is on enhancing students\' theoretical knowledge and practical skills related to the Conservation of Plasma Nutfah, including critical thinking, problem-solving, and collaborative abilities. The research method follows a quantitative descriptive design, with data gathered through questionnaires to capture students\' perceptions of the project\'s benefits and effectiveness. The participants in the study were students enrolled in the Conservation of Plasma Nutfah course and actively involved in the field project in Muaro Jambi. The analysis measured both the level of satisfaction and the achievement of learning objectives, particularly in applying conservation theory in practical, real-world contexts. The findings revealed that implementing PjBL significantly improved students\' understanding of Conservation of Plasma Nutfah concepts and boosted their learning motivation.\nFurthermore, students indicated that the case study project offered significant practical experience in autonomous and collaborative problem-solving with genetic resource conservation concerns. Nonetheless, specific issues were observed, especially in project teams\' time management and task coordination. The study concludes that PjBL effectively enhances academic competence and practical skills. ', ' Case Study, Muaro Jambi, Project-Based Learning, PjBL, Plasma Nutfah Conservation, Project-Based Education.', 'Rainiyati', 289, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS271-Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS271-Sarah Fiebrina Heraningsih.pdf', '2024-10-27 07:01:15', '2024-10-27 07:05:36'),
(272, 'big_data_analytics', 'oral presentation', 'Estimation Of Parameters on The Number of Malaria Patients in Indonesia Using the Poisson Regression Method', 'Gusmi Kholijah, Khairul Alim, Uni Baroroh Husnudin, M. Rafly Maretha', 'Mathematics Study Programme', 'Health is an aspect of concern, because health is a benchmark in the welfare of society. Health means that health in all forms is a concern, especially endemic diseases. Currently, one of the endemic diseases in Indonesia is malaria. This disease also puts Indonesia in second place as a country with malaria in Southeast Asia. Malaria is still widely spread in Indonesia. Malaria is still widely found in various regions in Indonesia. This malaria disease that attacks the sufferer is caused by various influencing factors, namely education, community income, place of defecation, sewerage, drinking water source, poverty level and knowledge possessed by the community about malaria. These variables are said to be predictor variables that cause the number of malaria sufferers to occur, which is said to be the response variable. Then the number of cases of malaria in an area follows a Poisson distribution which is influenced by several predictor variables. The observation area of interest in the number of malaria sufferers in Indonesia consists of 34 provinces. This parameter estimation will produce a model of the number of malaria sufferers in Indonesia. The variables formed are used as a consideration in the number of malaria sufferers.', 'Malaria; Regresi Poisson', 'M. Rafly Maretha', 293, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS272-Gusmi Kholijah.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS272-Gusmi Kholijah.pdf', '2024-10-27 10:54:07', '2024-10-27 15:00:50'),
(273, 'big_data_analytics', 'oral presentation', 'Training on Poisson RegressionAnalysis for Final Year Students at the Faculty of Health Sciences, Adiwangsa University Jambi to Improve the Quality of Thesis Writing ', 'Gusmi Kholijah, Corry Sormin, Gusmanely. Z, Niken Rarasti, Khairul Alim, Ario Surya Trinata, Candra Rijaya, M. Rizki Albaihaqi, Olivia Cantica, Riska Fitriani', 'Mathematics Study Programme, Universitas Jambi', 'Graduates from higher education institutions are expected to become agents of change and make tangible contributions to society. Universities, as providers of higher education, have an obligation to maintain the quality of their graduates. In accreditation assessment criteria, factors such as scientific publications, products/services, and the outputs of student research or community service also play a role in evaluating the quality of education and graduates from an institution. Therefore, the obligation to conduct research and community service lies not only with faculty but also with students. This requirement demonstrates that the research and community service carried out by students must utilize appropriate methods, data analysis, and decision-making. This issue is also faced by students at the Faculty of Health Sciences at Universitas Adiwangsa Jambi. Therefore, a training session on Poisson Regression Analysis was organized for final-year students at the Faculty of Health Sciences to improve the quality of their thesis writing as a form of community service by faculty from Universitas Jambi. The activities included workshops and hands-on analysis practice using R software. Based on the evaluation results, the activity received a score of 3.64 on a 4-point scale, indicating that the community service activity was conducted very well.', 'community service, poisson regression analysis, software R', 'Ario Surya Trinata', 293, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS273-Gusmi Kholijah.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS273-Gusmi Kholijah.pdf', '2024-10-27 10:56:47', '2024-10-27 15:01:32'),
(274, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Jambi Kritis Air Tahun 2033', 'Harmes, Muhammad Ikhsan', 'Universitas Jamvi', 'KOTA JAMBI KRISIS AIR TAHUN 2033\nHarmes*1, Muhammad Ikhsan2\n1 Program Study Teknik Sipil Fakultas Sains dan Teknologi, Universitas Jambi\n2 Program Study Teknik Lingkungan Fakultas Sains dan Teknologi, Universitas Jambi\n*)Corresponding author: harmes@unja.ac.id\n\nABSTRACT\n\nNational policy in spatial planning has been implemented massively since Law No.26/2007 was enacted. One of the functions the spatial plan is directing ground water management, especially water catchment areas.  The implementation of the Jambi city spatial plan, shows that there are inconsistencies in several landuses that are also water catchment areas. Anticipating the possibility deviation of landuses is important to maintain the availability of ground water for the society in the future. The purpose of this study was to determine the spatial distribution of potential of water catchment areas and its relationship to the Jambi City spatial plan. The research method used scoring and spatial weighted overlay techniques. Geopatial data that use as input  are the land use, slope, soil type and rainfall, the spatial pattern plan of protected and cultivated areas. Stage of the overlay process uses geographic information system ie. geospatial data compilation, processing and preparation, scoring and weighting, spatial and statistical analysis, discussion. This research shows that the condition of natural normal water catchment area is 164.79 ha or 1.12% located in the southern and east part of the city.  The critical is 235 ha or 1.60%, scattered in Alam Barajo, Pelayangan and Danau Teluk sub-districts. Moderately critical condition is 3,548 ha or 24.06%, spread across the southern part of the city in Kota Baru and Alam Barajo. Very critical area of 8,132.28 ha or 55.14%, covering most of Jambi City from the western part of Paal Merah, South Jambi, Jelutung, Pasar Jambi, Danau Sipin and Telanai Pura and Alam Barajo. The potential of water catchment areas in Jambi City is dominant very critical.\n\nKeywords: Critical Water catchment area, Jambi, spatial pattern, overlay, Spatial analysis.\n\nABSTRAK\nKebijakan nasional penataan ruang berupa yang diwujudkan dalam bentuk rencana tata ruang wilayah diimplementasikan secara massif sejak UU No.26/2007 ditetapkan. Salah satu fungsi ruang wilayah yang atur adalah tata ruang air, khususnya daerah resapan air pada bermacam bentuk peruntukan ruang.  Pelaksanaan perda RTRW No. 09/2013 Kota Jambi yang dilakukan monitoring pemanfaatan ruangnya menunjukkan terjadi inkonsistensi pemanfaatan ruang pada beberapa kawasan yang sekaligus sebagai daerah resapan air. Kawasan bervegetasi dengan fungsi sebagai pengatur tata air berubah ke penggunaan lain yang lebih intensif. Antisipasi adanya kemungkinan simpangan pemanfaatan ruang penting dilakukan untuk menjaga ketersediaan sumber air bagi penduduk pada masa yang akan datang. Penelitian ini ditujukan untuk menganalisis daerah resapan air dalam rangka perwujudan tata ruang wilayah Kota Jambi tahun 2033. Metode penelitian menggunakan teknik scoring dan spatial weighted overlay. Variabel penelitian meliputi penggunaan lahan aktual, kemiringan lahan, jenis tanah dan curah hujan, pola ruang kawasan lindung dan budidaya. Proses overlay menggunakan sistem informasi geografis. Tahapan riset meliputi kompilasi data geospasial, pengolahan dan penyiapan data geospasial, skoring dan pembobotan, analisis spasial dan statistik, pengambilan kesimpulan. Penelitian ini menunjukkan kondisi daerah resapan air normal alami seluas 164,79 ha atau 1,12% berlokasi di wilayah selatan kota dan sebagian kecil di bagian timur.  Kondisi mulai kritis seluas 235 ha atau 1,60%, tersebar di kecamatan Alam Barajo, Pelayangan dan Danau Teluk. Kondisi agak kritis seluas 3.548 atau 24,06%, tersebar disebagian Selatan kota di kecamatan Kota Baru dan Alam Barajo. Kondisi sangat kritis seluas 8.132,28 ha atau 55,14%, meliputi sebagian besar Kota Jambi mulai dari bagian barat kecamatan Paal Merah, Jambi Selatan, Jelutung, Pasar Jambi, Danau Sipin dan Telanai Pura serta sebagian besar Alam Barajo. Potensi daerah resapan air di Kota Jambi dominan sangat kritis. Temuan ini menjelaskan bahwa krisis air di Kota Jambi akan terjadi pada tahun 2033 sebagai akibat dari rencana tata ruang yang sekarang diimplementasikan atau dapat dikatakan bahwa penyebab krisis air adalah perda tentang rencana tata ruang kota Jambi tahun 2013-2033.\n\nKeywords: Daerah resapan air, pola ruang, spasial analisis, krisis air, Jambi.\n', 'Critical Water catchment area, Jambi, spatial pattern, overlay, Spatial analysis.', 'Harmes', 255, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS274-Harmes.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS274-Harmes.pdf', '2024-10-27 12:44:53', '2024-10-27 14:56:43'),
(275, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Helium-Like Energy on the Hylleraas Function with the Variational Optimization Method Fminunc', 'Sri Purwaningsih', 'Universitas Jambi', 'A study has been conducted on the calculation of helium-like energy using the variational method with Fminunc optimization. Optimization is a term often used to refer to minimizing or maximizing a function. In terms of optimization engineering, it is closely related to the design of the function F(x), which is called the objective function. In this study, the variational method with Fminunc optimization was used to determine the minimum of an infinite multivariable function, where x was a variable, and f(x) was the function minimized. The function minimized was the expectation value equation of the helium-like system as the objective function to determine helium-like energy. Based on the results, helium-like energy could be obtained in accordance with the literature.', 'Optimization, Fminunc, Helium-Like ', 'Sri Purwaningsih', 283, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS275-Sri Purwaningsih.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS275-Sri Purwaningsih.pdf', '2024-10-27 13:56:42', '2024-10-28 01:23:14'),
(276, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'MT', 'ade nurdin', 'universitas jambi', 'In 2021, Jambi Province recorded a significant rice production, reaching 298,149 tons of dry milled rice. The production comes from 64,412 hectares of rice fields. In Jambi City, as many as 1,368 tons of rice are produced, mainly from the Orak Kemang area which has 103.07 hectares of rice fields, or about 7.5% of the city\'s total rice field area. The city is located in a lowland north of the Batanghari River, with a lake connected to the river at high tide. However, challenges arose when the irrigation gate in Kaligawe Kanan collapsed due to theft, which interfered with water management in the rice fields. As a result, the process of drying rice fields is highly dependent on water absorption, especially in soils with low permeability. To overcome this problem, Olak Kemang village plans to optimize rice field productivity through a wind power irrigation system. This initiative aims to develop more efficient irrigation systems, introduce new technologies, and reduce costs. with eco-friendly solutions. The participatory action research approach encourages community involvement, so that researchers and residents can learn and collaborate in dealing with drought problems. The program not only focuses on technical solutions, but also strengthens community capacity to address environmental issues. With structured stages from preparation to evaluation, this project is expected to have a sustainable positive impact on the local community and the surrounding environment', 'irrigation, wind power, Olak Kemang', 'ade nurdin', 298, 'rejected', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, NULL, '2024-10-27 15:50:30', '2024-10-27 23:25:20'),
(277, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'STUDI PEMANFAATAN LIMBAH POME PADA CAMPURAN ASPAL PANAS DAN DINGIN TERHADAP KARAKTERISTIK MARSHALL', 'ade nurdin', 'universitas jambi', 'Palm Oil Mill Effluent (POME) adalah limbah cair yang dihasilkan dari proses pengolahan kelapa sawit di pabrik kelapa sawit. Palm Oil Mill Effluent (POME) mengandung mengandung 95-96% air, berbagai bahan organik, zat terlarut, dan padatan yang berasal dari hasil samping proses pengolahan tandan buah segar (TBS) kelapa sawit untuk menghasilkan Crude Palm Oil (CPO). Proses pengolahan kelapa sawit menjadi minyak kelapa sawit (CPO) akan menghasilkan limbah cair dalam jumlah yang cukup besar (Kimia et al., 2004). \nSalah satu upaya yang dapat di lakukan untuk  memanfaatan kan limbah POME adalah dengan menjadikan limbah POME sebagai salah satu campuran aspal.  Tujuan dari penambahan POME terhadap aspal adalah untuk mengetahui   pengaruh Palm Oil Mill Effluent (POME) terhadap aspala pen 60/70 di tinjau dari Uji Marshall. kadar aspal optimum (KAO) yang di gunakan adalah 5,8 %. Berdasarkan hasil pengujian sifat fisik dengan menggunakan uji Marshal, Nilai stabilitas yang di peroleh dari kadar aspal 1142, 5 kg, VIM 3,7 % kelelhan 2,7 mm dan VMA 16,049 % \n', 'Palm Oil Mill Effluent,Uji Marshall ', 'ade nurdin', 298, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS277-ade nurdin.pdf', '2024-10-27 23:31:14', '2024-10-28 01:22:00'),
(278, 'digital_transformation_education', 'oral presentation', 'Penerapan PjBL pada Perkuliahan Metodologi Penelitian untuk Merancang Proposal Tugas Akhir Mahasiswa Matematika Berbasis Technopreneurship', 'Wardi Syafmen; Bunga Mardhotillah; Cut Multahadah; Gusmanely Z;', 'Universitas Jambi', 'The Department of Mathematics has achieved specific learning outcomes in the Research Methodology course, including the ability to explain fundamental research principles, formulate research problems, objectives, and structures, conduct literature reviews and synthesize relevant research cases, apply appropriate research methods and analysis techniques, and effectively prepare research proposals and reports. The research framework guiding faculty and student projects in the Mathematics Study Program at FST Unja focuses on utilizing and developing mathematics and its applications to support the conservation of local natural resources and environmental sustainability, based on science and technopreneurship.To align course content with research methodology, Research Methodology instructors face significant challenges, requiring effective learning innovations. This is because students often encounter various issues in research methodology courses that may impact their understanding and research skills. One effective innovation for instructors is to implement Project-Based Learning (PjBL). This study examines the application of PjBL in the Research Methodology course to support Mathematics students in designing technopreneurship-based final project proposals. The study sample consisted of 29 students, with data collected through observation sheets and tests. Data analysis techniques included identifying course needs and objectives, designing projects, developing syllabi and lesson plans, preparing assessment instruments, implementation and monitoring, evaluation and reflection, as well as documentation and publication. The results indicate that applying PjBL in the Research Methodology course enhances students\' ability to design technopreneurship-based final project proposals and increases student engagement in class.', 'PjBL, Research Methodology, Final Project Proposal, Technopreneurship', 'Wardi Syafmen', 300, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS278-Wardi Syamen.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS278-Wardi.pdf', '2024-10-28 02:28:17', '2024-10-28 02:50:53'),
(279, 'sustainable_engineering', 'oral presentation', 'Optimizing Rice Field Productivity in Olak Kemang Village through the Implementation of Wind Power Irrigation System ', 'adenurdin', 'universitas jambi', 'In 2021, Jambi Province recorded a significant rice production, reaching 298,149 tons of dry milled rice. The production comes from 64,412 hectares of rice fields. In Jambi City, as many as 1,368 tons of rice are produced, mainly from the Orak Kemang area which has 103.07 hectares of rice fields, or about 7.5% of the city\'s total rice field area. The city is located in a lowland north of the Batanghari River, with a lake connected to the river at high tide. However, challenges arose when the irrigation gate in Kaligawe Kanan collapsed due to theft, which interfered with water management in the rice fields. As a result, the process of drying rice fields is highly dependent on water absorption, especially in soils with low permeability. To overcome this problem, Olak Kemang village plans to optimize rice field productivity through a wind power irrigation system. This initiative aims to develop more efficient irrigation systems, introduce new technologies, and reduce costs. with eco-friendly solutions. The participatory action research approach encourages community involvement, so that researchers and residents can learn and collaborate in dealing with drought problems. The program not only focuses on technical solutions, but also strengthens community capacity to address environmental issues. With structured stages from preparation to evaluation, this project is expected to have a sustainable positive impact on the local community and the surrounding environment', 'irrigation, wind power, Olak Kemang', 'ade nurdin', 298, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', NULL, 'invoice/Invoice-ABS279-ade nurdin.pdf', '2024-10-28 02:37:26', '2024-10-28 02:46:15'),
(280, 'bio_technology', 'oral presentation', 'Isolation, Screening and Characterization of Potential Carbonatogenic Bacteria as Concrete Biofiller', 'Didik yulianto1), Nadya Bestnissa 2), Dharma Satria3), Hafiz Muchti Kurniawan*4), Soni Pratomo5), Harlia Febrianti6)', 'Adiwangsa Jambi University', 'Eight isolates of carbonatogenic bacteria were successfully isolated from the Bukit Bulan area in Sarolangun Regency, Jambi Province. These bacteria grew well on Calcium Carbonate Precipitation Agar (CCPA) medium and were capable of precipitating CaCO3, with indications of urease enzyme production. Qualitative selection results showed that several isolates formed visible CaCO3 crystals around their colonies, while quantitative selection revealed that all eight isolates could precipitate calcium carbonate in NB U/Ca medium. The BB3 isolate produced the highest amount of CaCO3 at 135 mg/30 ml, while the lowest was 102 mg/30 ml. Gram staining characterized six isolates as gram-positive (BB1, BB2, BB3, BB4, BB5, BB7) and two as gram-negative (BB6, BB8). The urease test indicated that the BB3 isolate exhibited the highest urease activity. All isolates tested positive for oxidase production, and the BB3 isolate demonstrated significantly higher catalase activity than the others. Four isolates (BB1, BB2, BB3, BB4) were motile and had endospores, while BB5, BB6, and BB7 were non-motile. X-ray Diffraction (XRD) analysis showed that the calcium carbonate crystals were in the calcite phase, suggesting that the BB3 isolate holds the highest potential for use in concrete biofilling.', 'carbonatogenic bacteria, Calcium Carbonate Precipitation, Isolation, , concrete biofiller', 'Hafiz Muchti Kurniawan', 244, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS280-Hafiz Muchti Kurniawan.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS280-Hafiz Muchti Kurniawan.pdf', '2024-10-28 04:04:55', '2024-10-28 11:59:27'),
(281, 'stem_education', 'oral presentation', 'Analysis of Students\' Initial Abilities in Stochastic Process Lectures Based on Learning Results in Statistical Methods, Statistical mathematics, and Mathematics Preneurship', 'Bunga Mardhotillah; Kamid; Nizlel Huda; Zurweni', 'Universitas Jambi', 'Stochastic process is a collection of random variables representing the evolution of some system of random values over time. In simple terms, it\'s a way to model systems or processes that change in a random manner. These processes are used in various fields. Stochastic process discuss about several important things such as random variables, state space, markov property, and ergodicity. Students\' initial ability in lectures of stochastics process  refers to the level of knowledge, skills, and competencies that students possess when they first enter a class of this lectures.  This can include their understanding of basic concepts in a subject, their critical thinking skills, and even their attitudes towards learning. This research aims to analyze students’ initial abilities in stochastics process lectures based on learning results in statistical methods, statistical mathematics, and mathematics preneurship. In this research, urgent aspects that should be evaluated are baseline knowledge, skills, and competencies. Understanding students\' initial ability is crucial for creating effective and personalized educational experiences that promote growth and success in stochastic process lectures.\n\n', 'students\' initial abilities; stochastics process, learning result; baseline knowledge', 'Bunga Mardhotillah', 301, 'accepted', 'administrator@unja.ac.id', 'letter-of-acceptance/LOA-ABS281-Bunga Mardhotillah.pdf', 'invoice/Invoice-ABS281-Bunga Mardhotillah.pdf', '2024-10-28 09:18:54', '2024-10-28 09:45:14'),
